{"term":"1956","caseName":"United States ex rel. Hintopoulos v. Shaughnessy","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1956/205","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - March 04, 1957 (Part 1)","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren5/oral_argument_audio/13290","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 205, United States of America, on the relation of Anastasios Hintopoulos versus Edward J. Shaughnessy.","start":0,"stop":19.2,"duration":19.2}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief --","start":19.2,"stop":19.436,"duration":0.24}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Long.","start":19.436,"stop":19.914,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"-- Justice, may it please the Court.","start":19.914,"stop":23.731,"duration":3.82},{"text":"This case it involves two Greek citizens.","start":23.731,"stop":28.978,"duration":5.25},{"text":"Both of whom were regularly engaged in the seafaring occupations aboard the same vessel, following their marriage in the late 1950.","start":28.978,"stop":38.907,"duration":9.93},{"text":"The petitioner wife about seven months after her marriage and after several arrivals in the United States found herself expecting their first child and came ashore for a medical checkup.","start":38.907,"stop":54.637,"duration":15.73},{"text":"During which time the doctor has indicated to her that she should stop travelling because it would jeopardize the well-being of the unborn child.","start":54.637,"stop":65.736,"duration":11.1},{"text":"The husband, nevertheless, continued sailing and only when the ship was again ashore did he stay ashore and for pleading of his wife until such time as the child should be born, going to the fact to the wife was completely alone here.","start":65.736,"stop":83.808,"duration":18.07},{"text":"Now, the petitioner wife gave birth to their American citizen child in November 1951 and in January 1952, in accordance with the then prevailing law, both petitioners applied for privilege of suspension of deportation in order to prevent serious economic detriment of their American citizen child pursuant to the Immigration Act of 1917 as amended, which provision of law had been enacted by a modification law in 1940, not for the purpose of giving special benefits to illegal aliens but for the purpose of protecting the interests of American citizens or legal American residents who were dependent upon these illegal aliens.","start":83.808,"stop":141.245,"duration":57.44},{"text":"I am anxious to make that distinction because of the subsequent events that come about with the new Act of 1952.","start":141.245,"stop":150.456,"duration":9.21},{"text":"Now, following their application for this change of status in January of 1952, they were accorded a hearing in May 1952.","start":150.456,"stop":163.231,"duration":12.78},{"text":"At which time, the Immigration Hearing Officer found both petitioners fully qualified for this relief they requested, that is suspension of deportation.","start":163.231,"stop":175.957,"duration":12.73},{"text":"But he decided that he would not give them this privilege despite the fact they were fully eligible for him in his own words because of the fact that he felt there was too great a reward to accord them because of the accidental birth of their infant child in this country.","start":175.957,"stop":193.446,"duration":17.49},{"text":"Despite the fact, as I pointed out before that the whole purpose of the Act of 1917 as amended, Section 19 (c) is to protect this very American citizen child.","start":193.446,"stop":207.257,"duration":13.81},{"text":"The counsel at that time took a -- that appeal from the adverse decision of the Hearing Officer, and it is interesting to note that the Board of Immigration Appeals did not act on this appeal until March 1954.","start":207.257,"stop":223.235,"duration":15.98},{"text":"Now, of course in the mean time, the Immigration Act of 1952 had been enacted on June 27th, 1952, it went into effect on December 24, 1952.","start":223.235,"stop":234.94,"duration":11.7},{"text":"And in March 1954, when the Board handed down its decision on the appeal, it affirmed the decision of the Hearing Officer, it agreed that the aliens were qualified for suspension of deportation but again denied them that privilege without really indicating any proper reason for it.","start":234.94,"stop":263.473,"duration":28.53},{"text":"Whereas I submit that under the Act of 1917 as amended and by a great number of decisions here in the Court handed down by the Board of Immigration Appeals itself, they are supposed to ascribe proper reasons for denying or granting this discretionary relief.","start":263.473,"stop":285.275,"duration":21.8},{"text":"As a matter of fact, I have highlighted a case of Judge Bandy that came down on December 24th, 1952.","start":285.275,"stop":294.129,"duration":8.85},{"text":"Specifically, because the fact that he went to great pains to show the exact procedure that was then applicable in a case such as the one that needs to be reported toward at this thing.","start":294.129,"stop":307.944,"duration":13.81},{"text":"Following to this adverse decision of the Board, I came into the case in the spring of 1954 and I made a motion to reopen.","start":307.944,"stop":317.89,"duration":9.95},{"text":"And at that time, for the first time, the Board in considering my motion to reopen indicated that it have also taken into consideration the restrictive evaluation for this privilege of suspension of deportation that had been formulated under the Act of 1952, which I respectfully submit was error on the part of the Board.","start":317.89,"stop":349.944,"duration":32.05},{"text":"And I say that because the Act of 1952 has the saving clause in Section 405, which expressly states that the Act 1952 should not be applicable to any applications for the privilege of suspension of deportation that were pending prior to June 27th, 1952, when the Act of 1952 was enacted.","start":349.944,"stop":376.007,"duration":26.06},{"text":"And it was on that basis that I was thereafter forced to seek a writ of habeas corpus in the District Court of New York.","start":376.007,"stop":384.511,"duration":8.5}]},{"speakerName":"Harold Burton","textObjs":[{"text":"Didn't you see --","start":384.511,"stop":384.941,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"And --","start":384.941,"stop":385.163,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Harold Burton","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that the Board had turned down this suspension before the Act of 1952 and then turned down again after the Act of 1952?","start":385.163,"stop":392.35,"duration":7.19}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":392.35,"stop":392.71,"duration":0.36},{"text":"They turned it down after the Act of 1952 was enacted.","start":392.71,"stop":397.803,"duration":5.09},{"text":"Despite -- but I am pointing out that in their second decision in response to my motion to reopen, that for the first time indicated that they were taking the -- the elements and evaluation for the privilege of suspension of deportation that had been formulated under the Act of 1952.","start":397.803,"stop":418.711,"duration":20.91},{"text":"They so stated in their --","start":418.711,"stop":419.934,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"Harold Burton","textObjs":[{"text":"When is it they first turned it down?","start":419.934,"stop":421.965,"duration":2.03}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"The first time they turned it down they -- theoretically, were premising it on the rules prevailing under the Act of 1917.","start":421.965,"stop":430.992,"duration":9.03},{"text":"But in that case, I contend, that they did not ascribe any reason for denying.","start":430.992,"stop":435.098,"duration":4.11}]},{"speakerName":"Harold Burton","textObjs":[{"text":"When was that?","start":435.098,"stop":436.141,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"That was in March 1954.","start":436.141,"stop":440.243,"duration":4.1},{"text":"As I have pointed out that they left at quite a long time to go by, during which time of course the Act of 1952 had come into existence.","start":440.243,"stop":448.24,"duration":8},{"text":"And I -- I believe that there -- there was unquestionably even in March 1954, the new rules in their mind when they affirmed the decision, the adverse decision of April 1952 of the Hearing Officer in New York.","start":448.24,"stop":464.671,"duration":16.43}]},{"speakerName":"Harold Burton","textObjs":[{"text":"There's nothing in this to show, is it?","start":464.671,"stop":466.441,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"No, but in the subsequent decision of May 1954, I -- they -- they expressly indicate that they are influenced by the Act of 1952.","start":466.441,"stop":478.868,"duration":12.43},{"text":"As the late Judge Frank also points out in his dissenting opinion in the court below.","start":478.868,"stop":485.835,"duration":6.97}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"When did the Hearing Officer first denied?","start":485.835,"stop":488.35,"duration":2.52}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"The Hearing Officer first denied this case in May -- on May 29th, 1952.","start":488.35,"stop":494.725,"duration":6.38}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"That's before 1952 Act?","start":494.725,"stop":496.433,"duration":1.71}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right, sir.","start":496.433,"stop":497.901,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"There is now, based on the 1917 Act.","start":497.901,"stop":500.986,"duration":3.08}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"It was supposed to be, yes.","start":500.986,"stop":502.715,"duration":1.73},{"text":"And --","start":502.715,"stop":507.564,"duration":4.85}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Long, if we should agree with you, what would be the position, legal position of your clients?","start":507.564,"stop":514.466,"duration":6.9}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if you should agree with me then -- then of course my clients, having been found eligible by the very findings of the Hearing Officer himself for the privilege of suspension of deportation under the Act of 1917.","start":514.466,"stop":532.115,"duration":17.65},{"text":"They would then of course have the case remanded to the Board of Immigration Appeals for a finding consistent with such a decision on the part of this Court.","start":532.115,"stop":541.635,"duration":9.52},{"text":"And thereafter, the Board would make a favorable recommendation to Congress for suspension of deportation under the Act of 1917, applicable to these petitioners and the Congress would in due course act upon that recommendation.","start":541.635,"stop":558.967,"duration":17.33}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"If we should remand it then would there be any discretion in the Attorney General in this matter or do you consider that on the findings of the Hearing Officer and original finding of the Board that the Attorney General would be bound?","start":558.967,"stop":579.425,"duration":20.46}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'll come to that later in my brief, Mr. --","start":579.425,"stop":581.788,"duration":2.36}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"You -- you go right ahead.","start":581.788,"stop":582.629,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"-- Mr. Chief Justice.","start":582.629,"stop":582.774,"duration":0.14}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Don't -- don't bother answering that.","start":582.774,"stop":584.22,"duration":1.45}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm anxious to make that distinction because of my learned opponent has placed a lot of weight on the Jay versus Boyd decision of this Court.","start":584.22,"stop":593.716,"duration":9.5}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"But please do it in your own --","start":593.716,"stop":595.105,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":595.105,"stop":595.128,"duration":0.02}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- in your own time.","start":595.128,"stop":595.842,"duration":0.71},{"text":"You don't need to do it now.","start":595.842,"stop":607.351,"duration":11.51}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, I respect the --","start":607.351,"stop":607.823,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask -- may I just ask this --","start":607.823,"stop":609.55,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":609.55,"stop":609.748,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that your argument means that whatever may be derived -- that nothing may be derived from the policy governing disposition in 1952?","start":609.748,"stop":623.93,"duration":14.18}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, naturally, if the 1952 Act prevails in this case there will be no benefit at all to the petitioners because of the additional words in his discretion.","start":623.93,"stop":634.943,"duration":11.01}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I am talking about assuming -- the Chief Justice's question, assuming you prevail in your view, does that mean that the policy that it -- that 1952 must be shut out of the consciousness of all the authorities?","start":634.943,"stop":650.709,"duration":15.77}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Precisely, Your Honor.","start":650.709,"stop":652.21,"duration":1.5},{"text":"Yes.","start":652.21,"stop":653.085,"duration":0.88},{"text":"And that is the exact point that was held by the late Judge Frank in the Circuit Court of New York.","start":653.085,"stop":658.889,"duration":5.8}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, then --","start":658.889,"stop":659.373,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That is as a matter of construction, isn't it?","start":659.373,"stop":662.54,"duration":3.17},{"text":"That is as a matter of construction (Voice Overlap)","start":662.54,"stop":665.3,"duration":2.76}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, now, that's a -- that's an interesting question, Mr. Justice Frankfurter, because there have been cases that I have cited in my brief here which point out that if the alien is eligible for discretionary relief under the old Act, a denial of that discretionary relief must offer justification.","start":665.3,"stop":691.551,"duration":26.25},{"text":"Otherwise, of course, there is an arbitrary and capricious act on the part of the Board which would be subject to an appeal.","start":691.551,"stop":697.018,"duration":5.47}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What I meant is that Congress different things put before?","start":697.018,"stop":701.443,"duration":4.42}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Congress has different things under the new Act and of course --","start":701.443,"stop":703.818,"duration":2.38}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But was not relating to prior --","start":703.818,"stop":706.259,"duration":2.44}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"But it expressly exempts prior cases under its own saving clause.","start":706.259,"stop":709.932,"duration":3.67},{"text":"That is precisely my point.","start":709.932,"stop":710.194,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What I want to know is that's your argument?","start":710.194,"stop":712.067,"duration":1.87},{"text":"What I want to know is that whether Congress would have to -- is there -- are there constitutional issues lurking which will lead to one construction or rather another?","start":712.067,"stop":721.734,"duration":9.67},{"text":"That's my real question.","start":721.734,"stop":723.491,"duration":1.76}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Under the old law?","start":723.491,"stop":729.269,"duration":5.78}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there -- are there -- are there constitutional question which would have to be based at the construction other than that for which you contend?","start":729.269,"stop":743.529,"duration":14.26}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, as I have pointed out here --","start":743.529,"stop":746.346,"duration":2.82}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't mean to argue it.","start":746.346,"stop":747.438,"duration":1.09},{"text":"I just want to know whether your contention is that this raises constitutional question and therefore the statute must be very restrictively -- therefore the --","start":747.438,"stop":754.811,"duration":7.37}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"I think there -- there is a constitutional --","start":754.811,"stop":756.12,"duration":1.31}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":756.12,"stop":756.649,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"-- question there.","start":756.649,"stop":757.13,"duration":0.48},{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":757.13,"stop":771.857,"duration":14.73},{"text":"When the District Court handed down its decision in 1955, the District Judge acknowledged that the Board of Immigration Appeals had been influenced by the Act of 1952 and took the position that the Attorney General could take into account the new standard laid down by Congress.","start":771.857,"stop":794.927,"duration":23.07},{"text":"This is precisely the error of law on which I appeal to the Court of Appeals and thereafter came before this Court for a writ of certiorari.","start":794.927,"stop":806.186,"duration":11.26},{"text":"And it is exactly on this point that the late Judge Frank and the Circuit Court points out that the District Judge in recognizant of the Board took into account the new standard laid down by the Congress in the Act of 1952, was actually acting improperly.","start":806.186,"stop":829.777,"duration":23.59},{"text":"In that, he failed to recognize the saving clause and the rights preserved to the petitioners under that saving clause.","start":829.777,"stop":839.879,"duration":10.1}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- the examiner didn't, as I understand it, consider that he had to take into account the new provisions of the new Act, did he?","start":839.879,"stop":848.115,"duration":8.24}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, as a matter fact, we hardly examined a rule on this case in May 1952.","start":848.115,"stop":852.272,"duration":4.16},{"text":"The new Act was not --","start":852.272,"stop":853.497,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"For the Board.","start":853.497,"stop":853.863,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"-- in the picture at all.","start":853.863,"stop":854.262,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean -- I'm sorry.","start":854.262,"stop":855.186,"duration":0.92},{"text":"The Board.","start":855.186,"stop":855.442,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"The Board, of course, did not -- was not suppose to.","start":855.442,"stop":859.587,"duration":4.14},{"text":"I contend was not suppose to take into consideration the new standards at all.","start":859.587,"stop":864.605,"duration":5.02},{"text":"And the fact of the matter is that in May 1954, in response to my motion to reopen and reargue they acknowledged that they had been influenced by the new standards.","start":864.605,"stop":876.228,"duration":11.62}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And what I was getting at the theory of Judge Frank, his dissent as I read it is that he interpreted what happened as indicating that the Board on rehearing had felt bound by this new standard.","start":876.228,"stop":890.706,"duration":14.48},{"text":"And therefore, he said the case should go back to free the Board of that kind of a restriction which (Voice Overlap) --","start":890.706,"stop":897.377,"duration":6.67}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but he -- he felt that the Board had -- had made an error by virtue of allowing the new law to restrict the birth of the discussion -- discretion that they were suppose to exercise.","start":897.377,"stop":910.907,"duration":13.53},{"text":"And therefore that it was an illegal act from their part.","start":910.907,"stop":914.182,"duration":3.27},{"text":"Of course he was the minority opinion and the majority opinion sustained Judge Dawson of the District Court.","start":914.182,"stop":923.224,"duration":9.04}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's a different thing from saying that if the Board did not consider that it was restricted, that it could nevertheless not take the new standards into account, it's a different thing, isn't it?","start":923.224,"stop":933.35,"duration":10.13}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, of course, if the Board had never -- never gone into the question of the new Act and new standards, and had --","start":933.35,"stop":941.572,"duration":8.22}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"You wouldn't be here (Voice Overlap) --","start":941.572,"stop":942.71,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Precisely.","start":942.71,"stop":943.587,"duration":0.88},{"text":"Yes.","start":943.587,"stop":944.54,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Harold Burton","textObjs":[{"text":"Supposing, instead of a -- a new act, there's been new book published would it -- would this been all right for the Board to take that into theory?","start":944.54,"stop":952.271,"duration":7.73}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't think that this Court would be very anxious to endorse a policy like that either.","start":952.271,"stop":959.084,"duration":6.81},{"text":"Because I think that they -- the -- the Court is anxious to preserve whatever rights these petitioners are entitled to.","start":959.084,"stop":966.731,"duration":7.65},{"text":"And that was the whole purpose of the saving clause.","start":966.731,"stop":970.289,"duration":3.56}]},{"speakerName":"Harold Burton","textObjs":[{"text":"The saving clause is there but the application of it continues on and the person who would -- who administer makes up a discretion to the test of his knowledge probably and test of his right.","start":970.289,"stop":981.681,"duration":11.39}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"And yes --","start":981.681,"stop":982.181,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Harold Burton","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) read from books?","start":982.181,"stop":983.491,"duration":1.31}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"And is -- and is also bound to ascribe proper reasons for that under the saving clause.","start":983.491,"stop":990.411,"duration":6.92},{"text":"Now, that's -- that's the whole point of -- that Judge Bandy had made in his decision that I have cited here.","start":990.411,"stop":996.069,"duration":5.66},{"text":"That in proceeding under the old Act, there were certain definite rules and regulations that had to be followed by the Hearing Officer and by the Board of Immigration Appeals, step by step.","start":996.069,"stop":1005.695,"duration":9.63},{"text":"If they granted or denied a discretionary relief, they had to ascribe reasons for it.","start":1005.695,"stop":1012.946,"duration":7.25},{"text":"And that was not done here in the original decision.","start":1012.946,"stop":1016.361,"duration":3.41},{"text":"And then on my motion to reargue, they for the first time indicated that they had been influenced by the new standards of the Act of 1952, which I contend is an error of law because the Act of 1952 had no application here by virtue of its own saving clause.","start":1016.361,"stop":1033.701,"duration":17.34}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose the Board had out of its own thought, of its own imaginings, I don't know about it, its own imagination, not (Inaudible) at large.","start":1033.701,"stop":1045.931,"duration":12.23},{"text":"They first thought about these things and -- and put in the reason that it found in the policy of the 1952 Act.","start":1045.931,"stop":1052.475,"duration":6.54},{"text":"It says nothing about that Act or any either of you please know such as act had -- had been passed, would you fell that -- that in doing so, indulge it in a -- in conduct unrelated to the deposit of this question given?","start":1052.475,"stop":1071.163,"duration":18.69}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if they used language that would indicate that they were influenced by the -- by the new Act of 1952 --","start":1071.163,"stop":1078.497,"duration":7.33}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm assuming there was no such act in existence.","start":1078.497,"stop":1080.981,"duration":2.48}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1080.981,"stop":1081.07,"duration":0.09}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But that they -- but they thought about this matter.","start":1081.07,"stop":1084.535,"duration":3.47},{"text":"When was this in 1952?","start":1084.535,"stop":1086.343,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"The matter first came into the picture in the beginning in 1952, yes.","start":1086.343,"stop":1089.638,"duration":3.29}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose this kind of thing was in the area before and that they put it on paper as their own reasoning, although no act have been passed or is even in the legislative mill, would you have said that that consideration travelled so far out of bounds or what was relevant to the exercise of discretion that the Court would have to strike it down as arbitrary?","start":1089.638,"stop":1114.575,"duration":24.94}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I would -- I would take that position because I would -- I would contend that they were bound since they found the persons eligible under the Act of 1917 to either -- to -- to grant them the privilege that they had applied for.","start":1114.575,"stop":1131.459,"duration":16.88}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But is it -- is the granting of the privilege automatic if it --","start":1131.459,"stop":1134.793,"duration":3.33}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it's not automatic.","start":1134.793,"stop":1136.145,"duration":1.35},{"text":"But on -- on -- but they must ascribe reason for denying it.","start":1136.145,"stop":1139.418,"duration":3.27},{"text":"And unless that reason has a good foundation, such as a political antecedent or a criminal background, something like that, then I believe the courts would take the position that it has been arbitrary exercise of discretion on their part, but it is quite capricious.","start":1139.418,"stop":1152.751,"duration":13.33}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I agree with that.","start":1152.751,"stop":1153.144,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Particular -- particularly, what we bare in mind that the Act of 1917 is for the purpose of protecting the American citizen, relative of these aliens, not the aliens themselves.","start":1153.144,"stop":1163.738,"duration":10.59}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What was the policy that they have derived from the Act of 1952 which they then thought was relevant to the exercise of their discretion?","start":1163.738,"stop":1171.218,"duration":7.48}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the whole point is that under the Act of 1952, the Attorney General is given a much finer line of delineation in -- in exercising the privilege of suspension of deportation, it's strictly in his discretion.","start":1171.218,"stop":1191.273,"duration":20.05},{"text":"The words in his discretion did not exist before.","start":1191.273,"stop":1194.309,"duration":3.04},{"text":"And as a matter of fact, that is the point made by this Court in -- in analyzing the Jay versus Boyd decision when it handed down that decision.","start":1194.309,"stop":1202.452,"duration":8.14},{"text":"And naturally, under the Act of 1952 in adding those three words in his discretion, they have greatly restricted the granting of this privilege and have made it a much more difficult (Voice Overlap) --","start":1202.452,"stop":1215.562,"duration":13.11}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Where is the --","start":1215.562,"stop":1215.684,"duration":0.12}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"-- to accomplish.","start":1215.684,"stop":1216.629,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Where is the statute of -- that confined him under the -- where is the 1917 statute?","start":1216.629,"stop":1226.068,"duration":9.44},{"text":"I -- I've been -- he wasn't untrammeled before, wasn't -- he wasn't trammeled?","start":1226.068,"stop":1237.271,"duration":11.2}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":1237.271,"stop":1238.321,"duration":1.05},{"text":"On page --","start":1238.321,"stop":1238.352,"duration":0.03}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, what freedom did he have?","start":1238.352,"stop":1239.136,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"On page 14 --","start":1239.136,"stop":1240.532,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What page?","start":1240.532,"stop":1241.648,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"On page 14 of my brief, sir.","start":1241.648,"stop":1243.878,"duration":2.23}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"On the merit?","start":1243.878,"stop":1245.527,"duration":1.65}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1245.527,"stop":1245.667,"duration":0.14}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Speak on the merit.","start":1245.667,"stop":1246.536,"duration":0.87},{"text":"All right.","start":1246.536,"stop":1250.04,"duration":3.5},{"text":"Where is it?","start":1250.04,"stop":1252.044,"duration":2},{"text":"On top of the page or about --","start":1252.044,"stop":1253.198,"duration":1.15}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"No, at the lower part.","start":1253.198,"stop":1254.417,"duration":1.22},{"text":"There was --","start":1254.417,"stop":1254.842,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"In the case of an alien?","start":1254.842,"stop":1256.169,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right, sir.","start":1256.169,"stop":1267.922,"duration":11.75}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What page did you say, Mr. Long?","start":1267.922,"stop":1269.953,"duration":2.03}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"14, sir.","start":1269.953,"stop":1270.757,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":1270.757,"stop":1272.282,"duration":1.52}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"On the brief.","start":1272.282,"stop":1283.972,"duration":11.69}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, now, what -- forget about -- forget about actual reference to the statute, the 1952.","start":1283.972,"stop":1295.049,"duration":11.08},{"text":"What is it that, intrinsically, the Board drew upon that it couldn't have drawn upon in the Act that it stood in 1940?","start":1295.049,"stop":1308.228,"duration":13.18}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"They have -- but that's that, Mr. Justice.","start":1308.228,"stop":1311.02,"duration":2.79},{"text":"The Board, when they handed down their second decision in May 1954, acknowledged that under the Act of 1952, the granting of suspension of deportation was dependent on a more severe -- a more severe acid test by way of granting -- part of a personal fault.","start":1311.02,"stop":1340.415,"duration":29.39},{"text":"But in other words, it became not a matter of serious economic detriment but in their own words -- I'm reading it from page 12 of the argument where Judge Dawson says, \"The bill accordingly established the policy that the administrative remedy should be available only in the very limited category of cases in which the deportation of the alien would be unconscionable.","start":1340.415,"stop":1381.168,"duration":40.75},{"text":"Hardship or even unusual hardship to the alien or to his spouse, parent, or child is not sufficient to justify suspension of deportation.”","start":1381.168,"stop":1390.742,"duration":9.57},{"text":"That of course has made the standard for granting this privilege a very restrictive one and something very difficult to accomplish since the Act of 1952 came into effect.","start":1390.742,"stop":1405.516,"duration":14.77},{"text":"And on the other hand, under the Act of 1917, if the aliens were found eligible by virtue of good moral character and certain other rules of thumb that have been set -- set down by law and regulation.","start":1405.516,"stop":1424.108,"duration":18.59},{"text":"Then, because of the fact that it was the intention to protect the American citizen dependent, the privilege would be granted to the alien applying for.","start":1424.108,"stop":1433.29,"duration":9.18}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, may I trouble you, Mr. Long, to get out of --","start":1433.29,"stop":1436.262,"duration":2.97}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1436.262,"stop":1436.571,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the argumentation of abstraction to this extent.","start":1436.571,"stop":1441.097,"duration":4.53},{"text":"Judge Hincks, the court below agreed that suspension could not be determined on the basis of the 1952 Act.","start":1441.097,"stop":1452.055,"duration":10.96}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"That was right, sir.","start":1452.055,"stop":1452.948,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"They further found and concluded that, in fact, suspension was not on the latter act, is that right?","start":1452.948,"stop":1461.453,"duration":8.5}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"That was their position.","start":1461.453,"stop":1462.434,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1462.434,"stop":1463.158,"duration":0.72},{"text":"Now, what I want to know is this.","start":1463.158,"stop":1465.647,"duration":2.49},{"text":"What concrete considerations, not saying we decide this under the 1952 Act which has brought us suspensory -- non-suspensory powers but what item, what consideration stated, not as an abstraction that one is more than the other.","start":1465.647,"stop":1482.118,"duration":16.47},{"text":"What was the consideration, which in Judge Hincks' view was not an application of the 1952 standard but was a fact allowable to be taken into consideration until -- under the 1940 authority?","start":1482.118,"stop":1497.042,"duration":14.92}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, as I interpret the decision of the -- of the majority of the Court of Appeals, they take the position that the -- that the law is a living thing that is constantly subject to new interpretations and new analysis.","start":1497.042,"stop":1514.967,"duration":17.93}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"We often hear that argument that's --","start":1514.967,"stop":1516.437,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1516.437,"stop":1516.466,"duration":0.03}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the power of this Court.","start":1516.466,"stop":1517.331,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1517.331,"stop":1518.365,"duration":1.03},{"text":"And that the Board had every right to take into consideration these new standards.","start":1518.365,"stop":1528.576,"duration":10.21}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Not as standards.","start":1528.576,"stop":1530.217,"duration":1.64}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Not as standards but by way of a general consideration and they go on to -- to point out that they still believe that the Board did not actually base its decision on that but on the old Act, whereas Judge Frank makes a distinction that how can they possibly have taken into consideration these new standards when they had no business to do so by virtue of the saving clause of the Act of 1952.","start":1530.217,"stop":1561.52,"duration":31.3}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Judge Hincks says they didn't.","start":1561.52,"stop":1564.546,"duration":3.03}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, of course --","start":1564.546,"stop":1564.631,"duration":0.09}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Judge Hincks says --","start":1564.631,"stop":1565.437,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"That's why we're before this Court.","start":1565.437,"stop":1566.74,"duration":1.3},{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":1566.74,"stop":1566.926,"duration":0.19}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I know.","start":1566.926,"stop":1567.47,"duration":0.54},{"text":"Well, therefore, that's why you have to -- from my point of view, establish a fact that although he said they didn't take the standard into account, in fact they did.","start":1567.47,"stop":1577.299,"duration":9.83},{"text":"I don't mean to say that Judge Hincks isn't the most scrupulous man in the world if he -- I believe him to be, scrupulous as anybody.","start":1577.299,"stop":1585.001,"duration":7.7},{"text":"But what is it that led him to say, they took into consideration a fact or a factor that was relevant but not the law of 1952?","start":1585.001,"stop":1598.874,"duration":13.87}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"That's -- that's a little bit difficult to put my finger on, Your Honor.","start":1598.874,"stop":1603.331,"duration":4.46},{"text":"They -- they took the same position.","start":1603.331,"stop":1605.787,"duration":2.46},{"text":"Judge Hincks took the same position as Judge Dawson that the Board could recognize the new standards that had been formulated in connection with the Act of 1952 without --","start":1605.787,"stop":1630.494,"duration":24.71}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Taking them into account?","start":1630.494,"stop":1631.697,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Taking them into account.","start":1631.697,"stop":1632.68,"duration":0.98},{"text":"And of course that's the -- that's the puzzler that has caused me, of course, to come before this Court contending that there is an error of law there.","start":1632.68,"stop":1642.374,"duration":9.69},{"text":"I say of course that that whole -- that -- that any consideration whatsoever of the new Act or of the discussions leading to it in Congress have absolutely no part in -- in coming -- coming to this decision by virtue of the saving -- saving clause of the Act of 1952.","start":1642.374,"stop":1662.206,"duration":19.83},{"text":"And now, as I see it, of course, the Board of Immigration Appeals took approximately a year and a half, almost two years to come to its original decision in March 1954.","start":1662.206,"stop":1674.398,"duration":12.19},{"text":"When the new Act had been existence for the better part of two years and -- and they were bound to be influenced by it, and of course we're trying to avoid any admission of it.","start":1674.398,"stop":1685.087,"duration":10.69},{"text":"It was only when I moved for re-argument that I saw of course their -- their hand and they came out and admitted it in their new decision that they were influenced by it.","start":1685.087,"stop":1695.148,"duration":10.06},{"text":"And I contend that there was an error of law on their part.","start":1695.148,"stop":1698.807,"duration":3.66}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Where is the language of the Board in which they said that, Mr. Long?","start":1698.807,"stop":1707.793,"duration":8.99}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"At page 15 of the record?","start":1707.793,"stop":1710.264,"duration":2.47}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1710.264,"stop":1726.722,"duration":16.46},{"text":"In that first full paragraph on page 15 of the record, where they say in that line it is crystal clear that Congress intended to greatly restrict the granting of suspension of deportation.","start":1726.722,"stop":1743.201,"duration":16.48}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm looking for the past sentence, which we interrupt in this decision.","start":1743.201,"stop":1787.747,"duration":44.55}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What do you understand in the last sentence in that paragraph?","start":1787.747,"stop":1791.59,"duration":3.84},{"text":"You said the first sentence.","start":1791.59,"stop":1799.176,"duration":7.59}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean what it says in both cases, the decision of the Court?","start":1799.176,"stop":1802.008,"duration":2.83}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"We indicated in our previous order.","start":1802.008,"stop":1808.783,"duration":6.77},{"text":"The respondents have established a statutory trial.","start":1808.783,"stop":1811.499,"duration":2.72},{"text":"What do you understand that to mean?","start":1811.499,"stop":1824.517,"duration":13.02}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that I -- I consider an -- an open admission on their part that they -- that they themselves have denied due process of law here because they're acknowledging that the respondents, the petitioners in this case, are eligible under the Act of 1917 and therefore should have been granted the privilege of suspension of deportation.","start":1824.517,"stop":1845.78,"duration":21.26}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that -- that statement implies that everybody who is eligible must have suspension granted?","start":1845.78,"stop":1853.861,"duration":8.08}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1853.861,"stop":1854.4,"duration":0.54},{"text":"No, I wouldn't make -- I would take that position here, Mr. Justice Frankfurter.","start":1854.4,"stop":1856.682,"duration":2.28}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you couldn't -- you can't take that, can you?","start":1856.682,"stop":1858.718,"duration":2.04}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":1858.718,"stop":1861.835,"duration":3.12},{"text":"Because under the Act of 1917 there -- there are certain -- certain considerations that -- that have to be acknowledged.","start":1861.835,"stop":1868.398,"duration":6.56},{"text":"Now, the whole point is that if the exercising of discretion under the old Act does not set forth proper reason, then of course you have the question of arbitrary and capricious conduct on the part of the Board.","start":1868.398,"stop":1886.412,"duration":18.01},{"text":"And that is what I contend here because having found the alien, the petitioners eligible under the old Act, if they denied them that privilege they have to ascribe proper reason for it.","start":1886.412,"stop":1898.723,"duration":12.31},{"text":"And no proper reason was ascribed when the Hearing Officer stated that they can't get this kind of a privilege just because of the accidental birth of a child in this country.","start":1898.723,"stop":1907.984,"duration":9.26},{"text":"The whole point is that that child is the one who was supposed to be protected under the Act of 1917.","start":1907.984,"stop":1914.325,"duration":6.34}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"There they originally ruled to suspend their -- they recommended against (Inaudible) suspension.","start":1914.325,"stop":1920.334,"duration":6.01}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right, sir.","start":1920.334,"stop":1921.606,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"May we then ask for a rehearing and they reconsidered it?","start":1921.606,"stop":1924.838,"duration":3.23}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":1924.838,"stop":1925.915,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose they had said that while some hardship is worth nevertheless we conclude it.","start":1925.915,"stop":1934.879,"duration":8.96},{"text":"The suspension -- suspension should now be exercised in favor of this applicant.","start":1934.879,"stop":1941.175,"duration":6.3},{"text":"They then said we are confirmed in this conclusion in the Congress instead of making us -- indicating we should be more merciful or -- or more generous in our -- in our disposition, it's indicated that in its policy it turned to be steeper.","start":1941.175,"stop":1960.417,"duration":19.24},{"text":"So instead of reconsidering, we are confirmed.","start":1960.417,"stop":1963.466,"duration":3.05},{"text":"Suppose they've said that would you have a case?","start":1963.466,"stop":1965.969,"duration":2.5}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I would say yes.","start":1965.969,"stop":1968.271,"duration":2.3},{"text":"I would -- I would say yes because I would say that they have no right to consider the -- the new Act of Congress or by virtue of its -- of its saving clause judgment.","start":1968.271,"stop":1977.275,"duration":9}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I should be with you without question.","start":1977.275,"stop":1979.858,"duration":2.58},{"text":"I'm not saying I'm -- I'm against you even though my question is indicating I'm trying to be against you.","start":1979.858,"stop":1984.87,"duration":5.01},{"text":"But I should be with you clearly if they had originally ordered that suspension -- the recommended suspension.","start":1984.87,"stop":1996.134,"duration":11.26},{"text":"And then the Government had come in and said, \"Look, Congress vindicated you but as much as we saw, the word isn't mine but that (Voice Overlap) --","start":1996.134,"stop":2003.578,"duration":7.44}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right, sir.","start":2003.578,"stop":2006.79,"duration":3.21}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And then they said, \"Well, in light of that, we now realize we have been too easygoing.","start":2006.79,"stop":2013.103,"duration":6.31},{"text":"That we now see that -- although we act under the old Act, we shouldn't be so easygoing.”","start":2013.103,"stop":2018.146,"duration":5.04},{"text":"I think that would be wonderful, but if they denied suspension and then say we are confirmed in this conclusion by what is indicated that's not meant to be an alleviation but a harshening, if you will, of the requirement.","start":2018.146,"stop":2035.042,"duration":16.9}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2035.042,"stop":2038.814,"duration":3.77}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't see that they didn't fairly acted on that.","start":2038.814,"stop":2042.201,"duration":3.39},{"text":"They simply found confirmation that there shouldn't be any easier going than they were in their original conclusion.","start":2042.201,"stop":2047.911,"duration":5.71}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, as I have indicated in my brief, I have many number of cases cited of the Board itself that shows -- that each of which shows that in granting suspension of deportation, time after time, they were going on the basis of protecting the American citizen or legal resident alien dependents of the aliens.","start":2047.911,"stop":2069.382,"duration":21.47}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose they haven't granted a rehearing?","start":2069.382,"stop":2072.92,"duration":3.54},{"text":"Well then granted a rehearing, they wouldn't have to give a rehearing or do they?","start":2072.92,"stop":2076.317,"duration":3.4}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"No, they don't have to.","start":2076.317,"stop":2077.425,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose they haven't granted the rehearing, what would be your position?","start":2077.425,"stop":2084.069,"duration":6.64}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"That they were acting on arbitrary and capricious manner.","start":2084.069,"stop":2085.949,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"On the original one?","start":2085.949,"stop":2087.36,"duration":1.41},{"text":"On the original --","start":2087.36,"stop":2090.065,"duration":2.7}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that their -- their complete failure on their part to -- to exercise proper discretion.","start":2090.065,"stop":2094.525,"duration":4.46}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"In the original order?","start":2094.525,"stop":2095.753,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right, sir.","start":2095.753,"stop":2096.234,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I see.","start":2096.234,"stop":2097.069,"duration":0.84},{"text":"Oh, well.","start":2097.069,"stop":2098.977,"duration":1.91},{"text":"Well, then -- then the gravamen of your position is not that they drew on the 1952 Act but that they got confirmation for what already was lawless?","start":2098.977,"stop":2108.622,"duration":9.64}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, of course I came into the picture after their first decision --","start":2108.622,"stop":2114.994,"duration":6.37}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":2114.994,"stop":2115.126,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and I contended, of course, that they have not properly exercised their discretionary powers after having found both petitioners eligible for suspension of deportation.","start":2115.126,"stop":2125.961,"duration":10.83},{"text":"And therefore, I ask for reconsideration, and it was in response to that that they then brought in the new standards.","start":2125.961,"stop":2134,"duration":8.04}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"They said we stand on that and we're strengthened in our view.","start":2134,"stop":2137.201,"duration":3.2}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, and we're strengthened our view in part of the new standard which --","start":2137.201,"stop":2139.302,"duration":2.1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What I'm suggesting --","start":2139.302,"stop":2139.49,"duration":0.19}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"-- of course I say was entirely improper on their part.","start":2139.49,"stop":2142.392,"duration":2.9}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What I'm suggesting to you is that if you convince the Court, at least one member of it about his concern, that their original examination was arbitrary and baseless in law.","start":2142.392,"stop":2156.278,"duration":13.89},{"text":"You don't have to worry about 1952.","start":2156.278,"stop":2159.184,"duration":2.91},{"text":"You don't have to worry about --","start":2159.184,"stop":2160.118,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2160.118,"stop":2160.321,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- their resort to 1952.","start":2160.321,"stop":2162.186,"duration":1.87},{"text":"On the other hand, I have the greatest of troubles, if you can't do that as to the original finding that that is cut from under because they find reinforcement.","start":2162.186,"stop":2171.401,"duration":9.21}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I have made that point in my -- in my brief, Your Honor, in -- in this respect.","start":2171.401,"stop":2175.424,"duration":4.02},{"text":"I have pointed out that an -- on the basis of their original decision, not having ascribed proper reason for granting the discretionary privilege after finding them eligible for it that there was an arbitrary and capricious act on their --","start":2175.424,"stop":2190.532,"duration":15.11}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I hope you --","start":2190.532,"stop":2190.831,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"-- part.","start":2190.831,"stop":2190.983,"duration":0.15},{"text":"And I cite several -- several court decisions that are strictly on that point.","start":2190.983,"stop":2194.938,"duration":3.95}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I hope it will seem to you -- desirably in the use of your remaining time that you deal with that a little bit, because if you establish that and you didn't bother about the 1952 Act.","start":2194.938,"stop":2205.223,"duration":10.28}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask one question, Mr. Long?","start":2205.223,"stop":2206.522,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2206.522,"stop":2207.074,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Did you, on your motion for reconsideration, suggest that the Board had in fact, in its first determination, applied the 1952 standards rather the 1917 standards?","start":2207.074,"stop":2219.152,"duration":12.08}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"I raised the question.","start":2219.152,"stop":2220.708,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- did you charge that in the motion or how did you do it?","start":2220.708,"stop":2226.665,"duration":5.96}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"I have to go back a little on my whole record on that, Your Honor.","start":2226.665,"stop":2229.522,"duration":2.86},{"text":"But as I recall in my motion for reopening and reconsideration, I did raise the question of the new standard set down by the Congress by way of pointing out the distinction and the importance of preserving the rights of the petitioners under the old Act as against the new Act.","start":2229.522,"stop":2250.598,"duration":21.08}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but did you affirmatively suggest that the Board's original determination, which as I understand it, came down to 1954, two years after the 1952 Act came on the books?","start":2250.598,"stop":2261.375,"duration":10.78}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2261.375,"stop":2262.367,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Did you affirmatively suggest that they had determined, made their original determination on the 1952 standards?","start":2262.367,"stop":2270.401,"duration":8.03}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I don't believe I did that, Your Honor.","start":2270.401,"stop":2272.554,"duration":2.15},{"text":"Well, the whole point is that the original decision of the Board as it came down in March 1954, affirming the decision of the Hearing Officer, acknowledged that these people were eligible for suspension of deportation but denied them that privilege without giving them any proper reason for it.","start":2272.554,"stop":2297.608,"duration":25.05},{"text":"And I contend, as I have pointed out in a number of decisions cited in my brief, that they were bound to give proper reason for denying this, otherwise they were acting in an arbitrary and capricious manner.","start":2297.608,"stop":2310.293,"duration":12.68},{"text":"I have cited --","start":2310.293,"stop":2310.664,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"In other words, does that -- does that go this -- along this line that the eligibility requirements having been met?","start":2310.664,"stop":2317.959,"duration":7.29}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2317.959,"stop":2318.382,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And conceding that discretion?","start":2318.382,"stop":2320.963,"duration":2.58},{"text":"Nevertheless, is vested that despite satisfying the eligibility premise is nevertheless discretion under the 1917 Act whether or not to grant suspension.","start":2320.963,"stop":2331.072,"duration":10.11},{"text":"If they're going to deny it, admitting the eligibility requirements were met, they have to ascribe reasons for the denial?","start":2331.072,"stop":2337.68,"duration":6.61}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Precisely.","start":2337.68,"stop":2338.512,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And your point was that that had not been done in the initial determination?","start":2338.512,"stop":2342.183,"duration":3.67}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right, sir.","start":2342.183,"stop":2342.965,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn't the trouble with that though, Mr. Long, that the examiner gave reasons and all the Board did was to say, we reviewed the examiner's report and agree with him.","start":2342.965,"stop":2354.318,"duration":11.35}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, of course I contend that the -- the examiner's reason were actually a hollow thing, a shallow thing that they were --","start":2354.318,"stop":2361.056,"duration":6.74}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But he gave them.","start":2361.056,"stop":2362.15,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":2362.15,"stop":2362.206,"duration":0.06}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"He gave them.","start":2362.206,"stop":2362.578,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"-- when he -- when he contended that -- that the -- it was an abuse to the detriment of people waiting in long -- in long lines on the quota lists.","start":2362.578,"stop":2375.057,"duration":12.48},{"text":"As I pointed out in my brief, when it's to referring to quotas that are oversubscribed to the -- past the year 2000, it's a -- it's actually a sham argument on the part of the Hearing Officer.","start":2375.057,"stop":2387.2,"duration":12.14},{"text":"Particular instance, when the Act of 1917 was amended in -- in 1940, it was provided that under these circumstances not more than 50% of the annual quota of these countries could be hypothecated by virtue of taking away numbers for people to whom the privilege of suspension of deportation would be given.","start":2387.2,"stop":2407.615,"duration":20.41},{"text":"And when you're speaking now of a quota for a country that is oversubscribed to the -- to pass the year 2000, it becomes a -- a completely academic argument because we are really concerned fundamentally under the Act of 1917 with preserving the right of the American citizen dependent of the alien and not the alien himself.","start":2407.615,"stop":2430.884,"duration":23.27}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And then you have to shift your ground somewhat because it isn't -- your position then would be not that he gave no reasons but that the reasons that he gave were inadequate and they should be reversed --","start":2430.884,"stop":2440.071,"duration":9.19}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Were inadequate --","start":2440.071,"stop":2440.271,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- as an abuse of discretion.","start":2440.271,"stop":2441.25,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"Precisely.","start":2441.25,"stop":2442.035,"duration":0.78},{"text":"As I pointed out when I say that when he -- when he makes a statement of this is too great a reward to give these aliens by virtue of the accidental birth of their child in America.","start":2442.035,"stop":2453.03,"duration":11},{"text":"I think that he is -- is acting into the tongue-in-cheek and is acting in a very arbitrary manner because we're not concerned about that, we're concerned about that very American child that was born here or be (Voice Overlap)","start":2453.03,"stop":2465.084,"duration":12.05}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That isn't all we are concerned about.","start":2465.084,"stop":2469.004,"duration":3.92},{"text":"You can't -- you can split up the whole Immigration policy which to me is full of outrageous objects.","start":2469.004,"stop":2476.767,"duration":7.76},{"text":"You can't just call out one consideration in the case of our system that has all the purposes, as I say hardships and cruelty that I think it has and say we must construe it merely with reference of their child.","start":2476.767,"stop":2494.284,"duration":17.52},{"text":"Otherwise we talk about writing legislation, otherwise big enough to deal with that.","start":2494.284,"stop":2500.472,"duration":6.19}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"No, but as the courts have held number -- a number times, Mr. Justice, if -- if they'd rendered denied this discretionary privilege under the old Act, they must give a good and -- good and bonafide reason.","start":2500.472,"stop":2512.719,"duration":12.25},{"text":"Otherwise, there's no question that their acting in a capricious manner.","start":2512.719,"stop":2516.336,"duration":3.62},{"text":"There you have that as recently as 1915 in the Mastrapasqua case which I have cited.","start":2516.336,"stop":2523.467,"duration":7.13},{"text":"But in 1953, you have the (Inaudible) case here in the district and then you have the (Inaudible) case in the district as well.","start":2523.467,"stop":2533.93,"duration":10.46},{"text":"Now, all of these have taken the position that unless the Board of Immigration Appeals gave proper reason for denying or granting discretionary relief, there was an abuse of discretion on their -- on their part which would be subject to judicial review.","start":2533.93,"stop":2552.075,"duration":18.14}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"A proper -- I understand something that's rationally related for the task of judgment.","start":2552.075,"stop":2559.689,"duration":7.61},{"text":"But I'm -- what I would do, I can assure you I do very different things in most of these cases.","start":2559.689,"stop":2571.05,"duration":11.36}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Roberts.","start":2571.05,"stop":2578.482,"duration":7.43}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"May it please the Court.","start":2578.482,"stop":2581.828,"duration":3.35},{"text":"I should like to advert briefly to some of the facts which were before the Hearing Officer and the Board of Immigration Appeals when they rendered their discretionary decision in this case.","start":2581.828,"stop":2594.867,"duration":13.04},{"text":"The petitioners applied for admission to the United States as seaman in pursuit of their calling.","start":2594.867,"stop":2601.453,"duration":6.59},{"text":"They were granted surely for the length of time their vessel was to remain in port and in any event not to exceed 29 days.","start":2601.453,"stop":2610.623,"duration":9.17},{"text":"They remained.","start":2610.623,"stop":2612.347,"duration":1.72},{"text":"A female petitioner did not tell the immigrant inspector that she was pregnant at that time.","start":2612.347,"stop":2619.011,"duration":6.66},{"text":"They never applied for an extension of stay and they never revealed their unlawful presence here until two months after their child was born.","start":2619.011,"stop":2630.105,"duration":11.09},{"text":"At that time and that was roughly six months after the female petitioner had arrived, five months after the male petitioner had arrived, they appeared at the office of the Immigration Service in New York and stated, “We are here unlawfully,” and they filed their applications for suspension of deportation on the ground that their deportation would result in serious economic detriment to their newly born child.","start":2630.105,"stop":2659.774,"duration":29.67},{"text":"The Hearing Officer conducted their hearing on May 29th, 1952, a month before the 1952 Act was even enacted.","start":2659.774,"stop":2673.331,"duration":13.56},{"text":"He found that they have established --","start":2673.331,"stop":2674.666,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought the 1952 Act did -- wasn't enacted from December 1952?","start":2674.666,"stop":2678.285,"duration":3.62}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"It took effect in December of 1952 but it was enacted on June 27th, 1952.","start":2678.285,"stop":2686.193,"duration":7.91},{"text":"The Hearing Officer found that they had established the statutory requirements for eligibility to suspension.","start":2686.193,"stop":2694.376,"duration":8.18},{"text":"He found that there was serious economic detriment to their child and that they were persons of good moral character and that they were not aliens ineligible to citizenship and the other items which the statute required.","start":2694.376,"stop":2706.717,"duration":12.34},{"text":"But in the exercise of discretion he felt that this bounty, the maximum bounty which the statute provided, suspension of deportation should not be granted to them.","start":2706.717,"stop":2717.75,"duration":11.03},{"text":"And instead he granted the lesser bounty of voluntary departure for which they had applied in the alternative if --","start":2717.75,"stop":2726.308,"duration":8.56}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"They were deported, well, because they came here unlawfully?","start":2726.308,"stop":2729.256,"duration":2.95}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"He found them deportable because they were really immigrants at the time of arrival rather than non-immigrants.","start":2729.256,"stop":2736.812,"duration":7.56}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Where?","start":2736.812,"stop":2737.384,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"He found that -- that they had an undisclosed intention not to depart with their vessel.","start":2737.384,"stop":2742.811,"duration":5.43},{"text":"And therefore, they were immigrants and needed visas which they did not have.","start":2742.811,"stop":2747.053,"duration":4.24},{"text":"Now, in -- in denying this discretionary relief of suspension, he stated clearly why he felt the petitioners did not merit this relief and his reasons are set forth in his opinion which is set forth in the record appearing at page 7.","start":2747.053,"stop":2775.266,"duration":28.21},{"text":"At page 9 of the opinion -- of the Hearing Officer's opinion he states, “It is not believed that as a matter of administrative discretion the respondent's application for suspension of deportation should be granted.","start":2775.266,"stop":2791.556,"duration":16.29},{"text":"They have been on the United States for a period of less than one year.","start":2791.556,"stop":2795.772,"duration":4.22},{"text":"They have no relatives in this country other than each other and their son.","start":2795.772,"stop":2800.275,"duration":4.5},{"text":"To grant both this form of relief upon the accident of birth in the United States of their son would be to deprive others who are patiently awaiting visas under their already oversubscribed quotas.","start":2800.275,"stop":2813.343,"duration":13.07},{"text":"It is noted also that neither respondent reported his and her presence in the United States at any time until January 1952 when they filed applications for suspension.”","start":2813.343,"stop":2825.212,"duration":11.87},{"text":"So that it cannot be said that the Hearing Officer ascribed no reason for the denial of suspension.","start":2825.212,"stop":2831.918,"duration":6.71}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Roberts, would you mind dealing with the point that my Mr. Long raised that I'm ignorant about.","start":2831.918,"stop":2837.756,"duration":5.84},{"text":"Suppose there are 100 illegally entered Greeks, would that affect those waiting for visas to come here?","start":2837.756,"stop":2852.102,"duration":14.35},{"text":"I don't mean merely on his mathematics but on generally?","start":2852.102,"stop":2856.342,"duration":4.24}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"As a matter of fact, Mr. Justice Frankfurter, in this particular case it is not the Greek quota which would be affected at all.","start":2856.342,"stop":2865.529,"duration":9.19}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry.","start":2865.529,"stop":2865.933,"duration":0.4},{"text":"I thought these are Greeks.","start":2865.933,"stop":2867.203,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"These are Greek nationals but the record brings out that the female petitioner was born in Russia and the male petitioner was born in Turkey, and under the Immigration laws it is the country of birth which determines the quota rather than the country of nationality.","start":2867.203,"stop":2883.606,"duration":16.4}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And Turkey has a very low quota.","start":2883.606,"stop":2885.736,"duration":2.13}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Turkey has a low quota and both the Russian and the Turkish quotas are oversubscribed.","start":2885.736,"stop":2892.739,"duration":7},{"text":"Although, they are not mortgaged nearly so heavily as the Greek quota.","start":2892.739,"stop":2897.526,"duration":4.79},{"text":"So that counsel's reference to the fact that this is a very impractical reason ascribed by the Hearing Officer is not -- is not accurate.","start":2897.526,"stop":2908.851,"duration":11.33},{"text":"Actually, I've been informed by the State Department that the -- the waiting list on the Turkish quota is until 1965.","start":2908.851,"stop":2919.592,"duration":10.74},{"text":"And apart from that I see the --","start":2919.592,"stop":2923.587,"duration":3.99}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll recess now, Mr. Roberts.","start":2923.587,"stop":2926.406,"duration":2.82}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - March 04, 1957 (Part 2)","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren5/oral_argument_audio/13352","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"When the Court recessed, I was -- quote a situation I should like to finish with that before proceeding.","start":0,"stop":12.417,"duration":12.42},{"text":"The mere fact that a given quota is mortgaged up to 50%, up until a year in the distant future, does not mean that suspensions which are now granted are charged up until the last year.","start":12.417,"stop":31.017,"duration":18.6},{"text":"We've consulted with the state department and find that it is the current quota which would be charged if suspension were to be granted in these cases.","start":31.017,"stop":40.372,"duration":9.36},{"text":"In other words, the -- the Russian quota would be charged with the female petitioner's number and the Turkish quota with the male petitioner's number, so that aliens who have been waiting for a long time on those quota lists would be prejudiced.","start":40.372,"stop":54.974,"duration":14.6}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That is in 600 of the -- of something like that at Turkish quota --","start":54.974,"stop":59.684,"duration":4.71}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":59.684,"stop":59.978,"duration":0.29}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"If any Turk national, Turkey-born immigrant as a deportation suspended the -- from the 630, that would be counted one and there are only 629 left?","start":59.978,"stop":74.711,"duration":14.73}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right sir.","start":74.711,"stop":75.426,"duration":0.72},{"text":"And of course that 50% of the quota has already been mortgaged, so that there are only available one-half of that 600 odd and some of those are taken up already by preferences.","start":75.426,"stop":88.17,"duration":12.74},{"text":"I won't --","start":88.17,"stop":89.403,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Which do you refer to when you say one-half of it's been mortgaged?","start":89.403,"stop":93.255,"duration":3.85},{"text":"I don't understand that.","start":93.255,"stop":94.9,"duration":1.65}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there have been certain provisions of law.","start":94.9,"stop":98.688,"duration":3.79},{"text":"For example, the Displaced Persons Act of 1948 which authorized the issuance of visas in fairly large numbers to nationals of countries with relatively small quotas and has permitted the issuance of these visas notwithstanding that this would exhaust the quotas but stipulated that not more than 50% of the quota for any one year should be exhausted.","start":98.688,"stop":123.057,"duration":24.37}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"I see.","start":123.057,"stop":124.88,"duration":1.82}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"And in -- in administering these provisions, the state department is careful not to charge all suspensions up to the remaining few quota numbers available because that would mean that no quota immigrant could get into the United States.","start":124.88,"stop":140.318,"duration":15.44},{"text":"One thing further before I proceed and that is the -- the standard of review available in cases like this I don't believe it is correct to say that the Board of Immigration Appeals must justify its denial of discretion to the satisfaction of a reviewing court.","start":140.318,"stop":164.778,"duration":24.46},{"text":"I believe the standard which has been laid down by the courts and which has been followed is that which Judge Learned Hand stated in the Second Circuit in the case of Kaloudis versus Shaughnessy, and I'm -- I'd like to quote just one brief portion from that opinion.","start":164.778,"stop":183.126,"duration":18.35},{"text":"That appears in the Government's brief at page 19, referring to the suspension power and you're pointing out that is a dispensary power, Judge Hand stated, \"It is a matter of grace over which courts have no review, unless as we are assuming, it affirmatively appears that the denial has been actuated by considerations that Congress could not have intended to make relevant.\"","start":183.126,"stop":217.202,"duration":34.08},{"text":"And I may state that the immigration regulations did require the hearing officer to state in his opinion of the -- or to discuss in his opinion the reasons for granting or withholding relief.","start":217.202,"stop":233.152,"duration":15.95},{"text":"There was no such requirement with respect to the Board of Immigration Appeals and in many instances, the Board simply adopts the hearing officer's opinion and merely has a one-sentence affirmance.","start":233.152,"stop":245.831,"duration":12.68},{"text":"And if the Board does not state a reason for denying suspension, which is a clearly an inappropriate reason, there is really nothing for the Court to review.","start":245.831,"stop":260.803,"duration":14.97},{"text":"Now, getting back to the reasons stated by the hearing officer.","start":260.803,"stop":266.424,"duration":5.62},{"text":"As I have pointed out he stated that it was the fact that the petitioners had arrived within the year and that they had no close family ties.","start":266.424,"stop":276.691,"duration":10.27},{"text":"And that to grant them this maximum form of relief would deprive aliens abroad who had been waiting for a long time.","start":276.691,"stop":284.728,"duration":8.04},{"text":"These were reasons why the maximum discretion was denied them.","start":284.728,"stop":292.699,"duration":7.97},{"text":"When the Board considered the case, it affirmed on substantially the same reasons which it stated in its initial opinion in March of 1954.","start":292.699,"stop":306.583,"duration":13.88},{"text":"It adverted to the fact that the aliens had recently arrived.","start":306.583,"stop":310.327,"duration":3.74},{"text":"By that time they had been here a little less than three years, instead of a little less than one year and the Board adverted -- adverted to the fact that they had arrived as seamen.","start":310.327,"stop":319.54,"duration":9.21},{"text":"But in essence it was affirming the hearing officer's decision.","start":319.54,"stop":327.471,"duration":7.93},{"text":"When counsel moved to reopen and to reconsider, the Board denied that motion on what seemed to be very substantial reasons.","start":327.471,"stop":339.4,"duration":11.93},{"text":"It pointed out in its opinion on reconsideration that it had previously denied suspension as a matter of discretion.","start":339.4,"stop":351.311,"duration":11.91},{"text":"It pointed out that it had found the aliens eligible for suspension under the 1917 Act standards.","start":351.311,"stop":359.98,"duration":8.67},{"text":"But that in the exercise of discretion it had not considered them worthy of this form of relief.","start":359.98,"stop":368.32,"duration":8.34}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Where -- where did it say that?","start":368.32,"stop":370.295,"duration":1.98}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"That is in the Board's opinion, which appears in the record at page 15, I believe.","start":370.295,"stop":379.134,"duration":8.84},{"text":"At the top of the page, near the bottom of the paragraph it says, \"After considering, on March 18, 1954, we dismissed the appeal from the hearing officer's decision granting voluntary departure and denying suspension of deportation.","start":379.134,"stop":402.13,"duration":23},{"text":"After considering all the facts in the case at that time, we denied suspension of deportation as a matter of administrative discretion.\"","start":402.13,"stop":409.946,"duration":7.82},{"text":"And then in the next paragraph the Board referred to the fact that they had indicated in their previous order that the aliens had established eligibility under the 1917 Act.","start":409.946,"stop":421.989,"duration":12.04}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Where -- where does it say because they were not being worthy?","start":421.989,"stop":430.721,"duration":8.73}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"In the very last paragraph on page 16.\"","start":430.721,"stop":436.59,"duration":5.87},{"text":"Upon our further review of the case of the two respondents, we adhere to our previous decision that suspension of deportation should be denied as a matter of administrative discretion.\"","start":436.59,"stop":448.627,"duration":12.04}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- I thought -- I must have misunderstood you.","start":448.627,"stop":451.032,"duration":2.4},{"text":"I thought you said that they stated in this opinion that they had originally denied it because they were denied their right because they were not worthy.","start":451.032,"stop":460.033,"duration":9}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that -- that I believe is implicit here.","start":460.033,"stop":462.119,"duration":2.09},{"text":"That --","start":462.119,"stop":462.48,"duration":0.36}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh.","start":462.48,"stop":463.51,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I -- I don't mean that they explicitly stated that we find anything wrong with these petitioners.","start":463.51,"stop":468.985,"duration":5.48},{"text":"That is not so.","start":468.985,"stop":469.816,"duration":0.83},{"text":"The Board found that they were persons of good moral character, else it could not have found that they had established the eligibility under the 1917 Act.","start":469.816,"stop":477.608,"duration":7.79}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":477.608,"stop":480.225,"duration":2.62}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"And in denying this motion to reopen, the Board set forth a very valid reason for so doing and that appears right here on page 15.","start":480.225,"stop":490.439,"duration":10.21},{"text":"Counsel's motion sets forth no matters of which we were unaware at the time our previous decision was rendered.","start":490.439,"stop":498.169,"duration":7.73},{"text":"So that it cannot be said that the Board's decision, denying reopening was arbitrary.","start":498.169,"stop":506.274,"duration":8.11},{"text":"What petitioner points to, is the next sentence in which reference was made to the 1952 Act.","start":506.274,"stop":515.695,"duration":9.42},{"text":"And as I should like to point out at a later part of my argument, I believe that that did not alter the judgment of the Board.","start":515.695,"stop":526.425,"duration":10.73},{"text":"Now, the facts, the factors upon which the hearing officer and the Board relied in denying discretion were the same types of elements which the Board had previously taken into consideration in other cases, since the 1940 amendment put this discretionary power into the hands of the Attorney General.","start":526.425,"stop":553.064,"duration":26.64},{"text":"And these were the very same elements which were vigorously debated when the 1940 amendment was considered in this connect --","start":553.064,"stop":564.003,"duration":10.94}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Let me get this now --","start":564.003,"stop":566.47,"duration":2.47}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Of the record?","start":566.47,"stop":567.419,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Page 9 of the record.","start":567.419,"stop":569.413,"duration":1.99},{"text":"(Inaudible) by the general doctrine of discretion to the exercise against (Inaudible)","start":569.413,"stop":583.759,"duration":14.35}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I think that that is about the only reason.","start":583.759,"stop":587.769,"duration":4.01},{"text":"There was something on page 8, somewhere toward the middle where the reference is made to the fact that the female petitioner's testimony regarding her intention at the time of her admission was somewhat evasive and contradictory.","start":587.769,"stop":603.094,"duration":15.33},{"text":"But I don't think that that was necessarily the reason it was denied.","start":603.094,"stop":607.59,"duration":4.5},{"text":"I think --","start":607.59,"stop":607.887,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) that they were both of good moral character?","start":607.887,"stop":611.283,"duration":3.4}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":611.283,"stop":611.831,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":611.831,"stop":615.17,"duration":3.34}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I think you're correct in that, Mr. Justice Brennan.","start":615.17,"stop":618.061,"duration":2.89}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":618.061,"stop":619.669,"duration":1.61}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Surely.","start":619.669,"stop":620.088,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I find in their reliefs (Inaudible) they had been in the United States for a period of less than one year.","start":620.088,"stop":628.723,"duration":8.63},{"text":"They had no relative other than each other (Inaudible) each of the reasons there to grab hold of this form of relief upon the (Inaudible)","start":628.723,"stop":657.549,"duration":28.83}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I think that that sums it up.","start":657.549,"stop":659.387,"duration":1.84}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, do you suggest that all those were reasons for the kind that were (Inaudible)","start":659.387,"stop":668.325,"duration":8.94}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe that these were reasons of the kind that Congress took into account when it first enacted this legislation.","start":668.325,"stop":679.431,"duration":11.11},{"text":"If I may develop that, the Immigration Act of 1917 and the Immigration Act of 1924, which were both effective at the same time were inflexible.","start":679.431,"stop":697.614,"duration":18.18},{"text":"For the most part they required deportation of all aliens who fell within the classification stated.","start":697.614,"stop":705.322,"duration":7.71},{"text":"And after they had been in operation for a while it was apparent that this very inflexibility resulted in extreme hardship in many instances.","start":705.322,"stop":715.913,"duration":10.59},{"text":"For example, there was no statute of limitations in the 1924 Act with respect to aliens who entered illegally.","start":715.913,"stop":722.986,"duration":7.07},{"text":"So that as happened very frequently, an alien who had entered unlawfully after July 1st, 1924 and who have might thought that his entry was perfectly lawful, and who remained here for many years, had married an American citizen, and raised an American family, and had established deep roots in this country when he came to apply for naturalizations some years later, might find that the examiner delved into his initial arrival and found that to be unlawful and deportation proceedings were instituted.","start":722.986,"stop":755.148,"duration":32.16},{"text":"And the Secretary of Labor who then administered the immigration laws, had absolutely no discretion, had no alternative but to deport.","start":755.148,"stop":763.851,"duration":8.7},{"text":"That in fact one of the items which was mentioned in the congressional debates was that with respect to criminals, aliens who were deportable as criminals, they could be relieved from deportation because either they could get a pardon or if the sentencing court recommended against deportation that was effective.","start":763.851,"stop":784.794,"duration":20.94},{"text":"But aliens who were deportable on technical grounds and who had been here for many, many years, and had roots here could not be relieved against.","start":784.794,"stop":793.87,"duration":9.08},{"text":"And throughout the debates runs this common thread, that here are aliens who are deportable on technical grounds, who have been here for many, many years, and whom we are powerless to help.","start":793.87,"stop":807.525,"duration":13.65},{"text":"The Commissioner of Immigration, while various bills to alleviate this situation were pending, was requested by joint resolution to stay deportation in cases which could be helped by this type of legislation.","start":807.525,"stop":822.753,"duration":15.23},{"text":"And there were some 2800 cases in which he stayed the deportation from Congress to Congress, while -- while alleviatory measures were being considered.","start":822.753,"stop":837.411,"duration":14.66},{"text":"In his report to the Congress, he pointed out that some 59% of these aliens had been in the country for more than 10 years and I believe some 37% had been here more than five years.So that throughout the consideration by Congress was the fact that there were aliens who had been here for a long time, and who had married American citizens, and who had begotten American citizen children.","start":837.411,"stop":870.746,"duration":33.34},{"text":"And there would be extreme hardship in having these people deported, especially on the narrow and technical grounds specified in the Immigration Act of 1924 because there was no statute of limitations.","start":870.746,"stop":884.981,"duration":14.24},{"text":"And the Congress for a long time was loath to grant this discretionary power to the Secretary of Labor, even with respect to these aliens of long residence here because they were a little afraid that this might act as an incentive to other aliens abroad to try to get in here illegally likewise.","start":884.981,"stop":905.56,"duration":20.58},{"text":"That's merely one of the elements that was mentioned.","start":905.56,"stop":908.142,"duration":2.58},{"text":"But when the suspension legislation made it's way into the Alien Registration Act of 1940, the Board was entitled to take into account the question of recency of arrival and it did not necessarily restrict its decision to aliens who had been here for a long time, but that was one of the elements which they could consider and did consider.","start":908.142,"stop":938.758,"duration":30.62},{"text":"And the decisions of the Board, some of which made their way into the courts on habeas corpus indicate that this was one of the factors.","start":938.758,"stop":947.318,"duration":8.56},{"text":"Now, as the Court of Appeals pointed out in this case, Congress did specify the standards of eligibility in the 1940 Act.","start":947.318,"stop":958.664,"duration":11.35},{"text":"Those were rules of exclusion.","start":958.664,"stop":961.381,"duration":2.72},{"text":"Unless the alien could bring himself within the eligible class, the Attorney General, who by this time had succeeded to the Secretary of Labor's responsibility, had no power to suspend.","start":961.381,"stop":975.931,"duration":14.55},{"text":"But if the alien did bring himself within the eligible classes, this did not mean that the Attorney General was required to suspend deportation.","start":975.931,"stop":987.527,"duration":11.6},{"text":"Then it was left up to the Attorney General in his informed discretion to determine whether it should be favorably exercised and if it should be to what extent, because the 1940 Act provided two forms of relief.","start":987.527,"stop":1002.162,"duration":14.63},{"text":"First, the lesser form of voluntary departure which had certain distinct advantages and then the maximum relief of suspension.","start":1002.162,"stop":1013.515,"duration":11.35}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But Mr. Roberts --","start":1013.515,"stop":1014.557,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1014.557,"stop":1015.176,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Am I correct that the 1940 amendment (Inaudible) discretion upon possible serious economic detriment to a spouse or parent?","start":1015.176,"stop":1030.166,"duration":14.99}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right, it -- it set up as the minimum requirements that there must be a good moral character for five years and that there must be a serious economic detriment to a citizen or legally-resident child, parent or spouse.","start":1030.166,"stop":1049.528,"duration":19.36},{"text":"But these were the minimum.","start":1049.528,"stop":1053.063,"duration":3.54},{"text":"Unless this was shown the Attorney General had no power and it did not follow that if these were shown then the Attorney General must suspend.","start":1053.063,"stop":1064.087,"duration":11.02},{"text":"And --","start":1064.087,"stop":1064.36,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Even though there were applying with a serious economic detriment (Inaudible) there were still a reservoir of discretion?","start":1064.36,"stop":1073.505,"duration":9.15}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that is our view and I believe we are borne out in that by the very terminology of the statute, which appears in full, in the Government's brief at pages 2 to 4.","start":1073.505,"stop":1090.475,"duration":16.97},{"text":"The excerpt from this Section which appeared in the respondent's brief did not contain the entire Act and I should like to point this out at page 2, moving about six lines down from the opening of the quoted matter.","start":1090.475,"stop":1111.356,"duration":20.88},{"text":"It says, \"The Attorney General may permit the alien to depart or suspend deportation.\"","start":1111.356,"stop":1118.712,"duration":7.36},{"text":"And in the rest of that very Section, the word shall is used on seven different occasions.","start":1118.712,"stop":1126.261,"duration":7.55},{"text":"For example, if the Attorney General, and I'm now referring to page 3 of our brief, if the Attorney General suspends deportation for more than six months then the statute says that a detailed statement of the facts and pertinent provisions of law in the case shall be reported to Congress.","start":1126.261,"stop":1145.935,"duration":19.67},{"text":"And if during the session of Congress or the next Congress passes a concurrent resolution, favoring the suspension, then the Attorney General shall cancel deportation proceedings.","start":1145.935,"stop":1159.525,"duration":13.59}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what standard (Inaudible) discretion beyond the pointing of economic (Inaudible)","start":1159.525,"stop":1168.676,"duration":9.15}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"The statute set up no standard, neither the 1917 Act nor the 1952 Act for that matter, set up any yard stick to bind the Attorney General in exercising his discretion.","start":1168.676,"stop":1184.782,"duration":16.11},{"text":"That was left to his informed discretion and I believe properly so because the Attorney General was chargeable not only with granting suspension.","start":1184.782,"stop":1197.339,"duration":12.56},{"text":"He was chargeable with the overall administration of the immigration laws.","start":1197.339,"stop":1200.25,"duration":2.91},{"text":"And there were many, many factors which he could and should take into account in weighing discretion.","start":1200.25,"stop":1208.485,"duration":8.23}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1208.485,"stop":1211.603,"duration":3.12}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"For example, the recency of the arrival, I believe, is a factor to be taken into account.","start":1211.603,"stop":1223.406,"duration":11.8},{"text":"The fact that the petitioners arrived as seamen, seamen as Your Honor understands, are granted certain privileges under the immigration laws.","start":1223.406,"stop":1236.41,"duration":13},{"text":"In order to keep commerce flowing, they are readily granted shore leave at being contemplated that they will depart with their vessels.","start":1236.41,"stop":1244.603,"duration":8.19},{"text":"But the seamen route provides a very easy route for aliens to enter the United States very readily and then stay here if they are not acting in good faith.","start":1244.603,"stop":1254.356,"duration":9.75},{"text":"And it's quite a problem in the administration of the immigration laws to -- to avoid affording incentives for seamen to stay here and remain.","start":1254.356,"stop":1266.442,"duration":12.09},{"text":"The acquisition of dependence very recently has been one basis on which the Attorney General has denied suspension in some cases even though --","start":1266.442,"stop":1278.967,"duration":12.53}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"In what -- what period from the date of arrival to the date of (Inaudible)","start":1278.967,"stop":1282.889,"duration":3.92}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"It was -- well, the -- the female petitioner arrived in July.","start":1282.889,"stop":1287.472,"duration":4.58},{"text":"The child was born in November.","start":1287.472,"stop":1288.538,"duration":1.07},{"text":"That's five months later I believe.","start":1288.538,"stop":1290.956,"duration":2.42},{"text":"And the -- the male petitioner arrived in August on his last trip.","start":1290.956,"stop":1294.708,"duration":3.75},{"text":"So, I think that's four months.","start":1294.708,"stop":1298.117,"duration":3.41},{"text":"At any rate it was a matter of a few months after they had arrived.","start":1298.117,"stop":1302.978,"duration":4.86},{"text":"So, that is one of the factors.","start":1302.978,"stop":1304.8,"duration":1.82},{"text":"I should also like to point out that the factors upon which the Attorney General's discretion must be based vary from time to time and the Attorney General cannot act in a vacuum.","start":1304.8,"stop":1317.153,"duration":12.35},{"text":"He cannot -- it cannot be expected to limit himself to those elements which were operative in 1940 when this legislation was enacted because much history has been written since 1940.","start":1317.153,"stop":1329.639,"duration":12.49},{"text":"We've had the war and -- and there were situations engendered by the war, which required the Attorney General in the exercise of his sound discretion to tighten up in certain classes of cases.","start":1329.639,"stop":1341.712,"duration":12.07},{"text":"And in the aftermath of the war, there were situations, the stowaway situation immediately after the close of World War II.","start":1341.712,"stop":1350.431,"duration":8.72},{"text":"We got a -- a situation which was intolerable and would have lead to the breakdown of -- of the immigration law as if we permitted it to continue.","start":1350.431,"stop":1358.716,"duration":8.28},{"text":"So that these are all factors which must be weighed and since the Attorney General has the closest touch with the overall situation, Congress left that it to his informed discretion to determine under what circumstances this maximum form of relief should be granted.","start":1358.716,"stop":1380.854,"duration":22.14},{"text":"And as I stated the courts have held that this power is a dispensary power.","start":1380.854,"stop":1389.363,"duration":8.51},{"text":"Last year, this Court, likened it did to the power of the President in granting a pardon or the power of the Parole Board in granting parole.","start":1389.363,"stop":1403.025,"duration":13.66},{"text":"And in reviewing the exercise of discretion, the Court has not set aside the administrative determination.Unless, as Judge Learned Hand pointed out, it affirmatively -- affirmatively appears that it was actuated by considerations that Congress could not have intended to make relevant.","start":1403.025,"stop":1424.707,"duration":21.68}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And I gather (Inaudible) to certainly at least relevant to the statute (Inaudible)","start":1424.707,"stop":1436.397,"duration":11.69}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that is our view.","start":1436.397,"stop":1440.025,"duration":3.63},{"text":"And I also suggest that every one of these considerations is geared not only to the background of the 1940 legislation, but is consonant with the practices under the 1940 Act.","start":1440.025,"stop":1458.949,"duration":18.92},{"text":"And as the Board pointed out in its motion and its decision on the motion on reconsideration, it is also consonant with what the Congress referred to in the 1952 Act.","start":1458.949,"stop":1476.201,"duration":17.25}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"In this case what are the similarities between this and the exercise of pardon or parole?","start":1476.201,"stop":1482.971,"duration":6.77}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"In this --","start":1482.971,"stop":1483.157,"duration":0.19}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Had you picked --","start":1483.157,"stop":1483.172,"duration":0.02}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"In this case both petitioners are violators of the immigration laws.","start":1483.172,"stop":1491.976,"duration":8.8},{"text":"They are deportable.","start":1491.976,"stop":1493.613,"duration":1.64},{"text":"That is conceded.","start":1493.613,"stop":1495.801,"duration":2.19},{"text":"In the absence of the exercise of discretion in their favor, the law requires them to be deported.","start":1495.801,"stop":1503.628,"duration":7.83},{"text":"So they come here or I should say they come to the Attorney General and they say they have met the standards.","start":1503.628,"stop":1511.545,"duration":7.92},{"text":"They are within the class to whom he may grant suspension of deportation.","start":1511.545,"stop":1517.663,"duration":6.12},{"text":"But it is a matter of grace.","start":1517.663,"stop":1519.699,"duration":2.04},{"text":"He need not and if he feels that the circumstances are such that he should not, he will not.","start":1519.699,"stop":1527.374,"duration":7.67},{"text":"I -- I believe that that analogy is a complete one.","start":1527.374,"stop":1531.316,"duration":3.94},{"text":"It -- it accords with what this Court said last year in the Jay case and with what the other courts have said Judge Learned Hand in the Kaloudis case and Judge Frank in the Adel case.","start":1531.316,"stop":1547.538,"duration":16.22},{"text":"So far as I know there has never been a decision which has held that this is not a discretionary grant.","start":1547.538,"stop":1557.232,"duration":9.69},{"text":"The cases have been -- have been uniform in the 17 years that this Section has been before the courts.","start":1557.232,"stop":1565.627,"duration":8.39}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Have there been any limitations at all placed upon the scope of that discretion?","start":1565.627,"stop":1573.088,"duration":7.46}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"There have been a couple.","start":1573.088,"stop":1575.29,"duration":2.2},{"text":"For one thing, this Court in the Accardi case, the first Accardi case held that when the Board exercises discretion, it must exercise its own discretion.","start":1575.29,"stop":1588.078,"duration":12.79},{"text":"It cannot be dictated to by the Attorney General.","start":1588.078,"stop":1590.675,"duration":2.6}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1590.675,"stop":1591.827,"duration":1.15}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"And on the second go around in that case it was found that there had been no such dictation.","start":1591.827,"stop":1598.552,"duration":6.72},{"text":"Other courts have held -- in fact this Court in the Christensen case, some years back, held that the Court cannot deny discretion on an improper basis of ineligibility.","start":1598.552,"stop":1616.851,"duration":18.3},{"text":"In the Christensen case, the Board had found the -- the petitioner was ineligible to the benefits.","start":1616.851,"stop":1623.93,"duration":7.08},{"text":"So, strictly speaking that wasn't merely a matter of discretion.","start":1623.93,"stop":1627.159,"duration":3.23},{"text":"It was a matter of eligibility but it adds up to the same thing because when the Court -- when the Board withholds its discretion on a theory that it has no discretion because of ineligibility, the Court has said that that is improper.","start":1627.159,"stop":1644.682,"duration":17.52},{"text":"There has been another case, which counsel referred to in the Second Circuit, the Mastrapasqua case, in which the Court had held that when the Board in classifying aliens and in determining aliens in various categories, who should not be granted this relief, hits upon a classification which bears no reasonable relationship to what Congress intended.","start":1644.682,"stop":1676.693,"duration":32.01},{"text":"That is arbitrary and that in effect the Board fails to exercise its discretion.","start":1676.693,"stop":1684.777,"duration":8.08},{"text":"But apart from this, there've been any number of decisions where the courts have stated, these are matters of administrative discretion on which we shall not intervene.","start":1684.777,"stop":1695.822,"duration":11.04},{"text":"And in fact, some courts have suggested that -- that this type of discretion is within the second exception to the opening sentence of Section 10 of the Administrative Procedure Act, and which states that except insofar as agency review is limited to agency discretion or -- or words to that effect, there shall be judicial review.","start":1695.822,"stop":1719.651,"duration":23.83},{"text":"The Ninth Circuit has held to that effect.","start":1719.651,"stop":1722.98,"duration":3.33},{"text":"I know of no decision which has stated that the Board must justify its exercise.","start":1722.98,"stop":1732.94,"duration":9.96},{"text":"Actually, it has been the reverse that the courts will not interfere, unless it affirmatively appears that the Board has acted upon considerations which Congress never intended to apply.","start":1732.94,"stop":1745.35,"duration":12.41}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And its -- its discretion must be individualized.","start":1745.35,"stop":1749.359,"duration":4.01},{"text":"It can't make a class determination.","start":1749.359,"stop":1751.477,"duration":2.12}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":1751.477,"stop":1752.856,"duration":1.38},{"text":"That -- that is so.","start":1752.856,"stop":1753.033,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It can't -- it can't say our experience has been that nationals of this country or our experience has been that seamen who come here in one way.","start":1753.033,"stop":1766.894,"duration":13.86},{"text":"It must be distinctly -- completely individualized --","start":1766.894,"stop":1771.21,"duration":4.32}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly.","start":1771.21,"stop":1771.341,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- is that right, Mr. Roberts?","start":1771.341,"stop":1772.396,"duration":1.06}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly, Your Honor.","start":1772.396,"stop":1774.051,"duration":1.65},{"text":"And as a matter of fact it was on that basis that this Court in the first Accardi case rejected the argument, that merely because the Board had granted suspension in cases which were factually similar, it abused this discretion in not granting suspension to Accardi.","start":1774.051,"stop":1793.42,"duration":19.37},{"text":"This Court held that that argument was frivolous and was properly disposed and as such by the Second Circuit because each case must be determined on its own base.","start":1793.42,"stop":1805.232,"duration":11.81},{"text":"And while there maybe similarities from case to case, as Mr. Justice Frankfurter pointed out, each case must be considered as an entity in itself.","start":1805.232,"stop":1817.364,"duration":12.13}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"How did the wife get into the United States?","start":1817.364,"stop":1819.752,"duration":2.39}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"As a seaman, sir.","start":1819.752,"stop":1820.89,"duration":1.14},{"text":"She was a seaman?","start":1820.89,"stop":1822.189,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1822.189,"stop":1822.623,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1822.623,"stop":1823.687,"duration":1.06}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"It -- it may seem --","start":1823.687,"stop":1825.507,"duration":1.82}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1825.507,"stop":1828.89,"duration":3.38}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"No, according to her testimony and we have no reason to doubt it, the -- the petitioner was a seaman of longstanding, I think about 15 years.","start":1828.89,"stop":1841.896,"duration":13.01},{"text":"And he met the -- and that is the male petitioner who was a seaman.","start":1841.896,"stop":1841.902,"duration":0.01},{"text":"And he met the female petitioner and wanted to marry her but his vessel was not going to touch at Greece for sometime, so she arranged to meet him in North Africa and he put her on as a seaman.","start":1841.902,"stop":1854.994,"duration":13.09},{"text":"He was the chief steward I believe and he put her on as an assistant steward.","start":1854.994,"stop":1859.926,"duration":4.93},{"text":"And she had made a few trips before this last entry on which she stayed.","start":1859.926,"stop":1866.114,"duration":6.19}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Roberts, of course it's legal to (Inaudible) but why is it significant that the legal (Inaudible)","start":1866.114,"stop":1884.548,"duration":18.43}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"I can only infer that the hearing officer felt that there might be a slight element of bad faith here.","start":1884.548,"stop":1895.917,"duration":11.37},{"text":"There have been cases in which the Board has denied discretion where an alien sought to gain time until he could possibly qualify for eligibility.","start":1895.917,"stop":1912.055,"duration":16.14},{"text":"Part of the statute, for example, confers eligibility on the basis of seven years residence, and where aliens who have been here less than seven years have contrived somehow by dilatory tactics or by evasion to muster that up seven years.","start":1912.055,"stop":1932.538,"duration":20.48},{"text":"The Board has taken that into account.","start":1932.538,"stop":1934.404,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The idea is (Inaudible)","start":1934.404,"stop":1937.459,"duration":3.06}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1937.459,"stop":1937.881,"duration":0.42},{"text":"And they couldn't --","start":1937.881,"stop":1938.522,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1938.522,"stop":1941.407,"duration":2.88},{"text":"No, they weren't -- they weren't eligible until they had a dependent but they were -- they were required to report because the Alien Registration Act, the very Act which -- which created this suspension provision required all aliens who are in the United States for 30 days or longer to be registered and fingerprinted.","start":1941.407,"stop":1966.079,"duration":24.67},{"text":"They might have been reported before the child was born (Inaudible)","start":1966.079,"stop":1970.593,"duration":4.51}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"They might have.","start":1970.593,"stop":1971.637,"duration":1.04},{"text":"Of course, that -- that's conjecture.","start":1971.637,"stop":1973.441,"duration":1.8},{"text":"If -- if the female petitioner had told the -- the immigrant inspector who examined her that she was pregnant and that she intended to remain here until her child was born, it's quite possible you might not -- not have found to her to be eligible for admission as a seaman.","start":1973.441,"stop":1995.579,"duration":22.14}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, suppose -- suppose even though they don't' want to run to the immigration naturalization division but they do like to get -- get some enlightenment.","start":1995.579,"stop":2006.784,"duration":11.21},{"text":"Suppose Russia wouldn't -- wouldn't take her.Suppose for some reason Greece won't take him, I mean Turkey won't take him.","start":2006.784,"stop":2018.643,"duration":11.86},{"text":"That's a possibility, isn't it?","start":2018.643,"stop":2021.215,"duration":2.57},{"text":"May I -- may I say this, that --","start":2021.215,"stop":2022.599,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":2022.599,"stop":2022.813,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"-- while -- while for quota purposes they are chargeable to the countries of birth --","start":2022.813,"stop":2027.604,"duration":4.79}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"They'd go back --","start":2027.604,"stop":2028.267,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"They go to the country of nationality.","start":2028.267,"stop":2029.619,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":2029.619,"stop":2030.132,"duration":0.51},{"text":"Well, Greece has been changing its mind about several things recently.","start":2030.132,"stop":2034.268,"duration":4.14},{"text":"Suppose Greece wouldn't take one or the other.","start":2034.268,"stop":2036.86,"duration":2.59},{"text":"What then if one has to stay here for six months, like nothing happens for six months, that's not an inconceivable situation, is it?","start":2036.86,"stop":2045.948,"duration":9.09}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think Your Honor --","start":2045.948,"stop":2047.118,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Will boats be allowed to stay here plus the baby?","start":2047.118,"stop":2049.63,"duration":2.51},{"text":"Babies (Inaudible) citizen might become a president of the United States one of this days.","start":2049.63,"stop":2054.574,"duration":4.94}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I think that in this case the Immigration Service has passports for both petitioners.","start":2054.574,"stop":2061.498,"duration":6.92}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I didn't seem to hear that.","start":2061.498,"stop":2064.129,"duration":2.63}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"So that that is not a question in this case.","start":2064.129,"stop":2067.034,"duration":2.91}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And the child can't be refused the passport because -- oh, I better not talk about what you may or may not refuse in passports.","start":2067.034,"stop":2072.771,"duration":5.74},{"text":"All right.","start":2072.771,"stop":2073.027,"duration":0.26},{"text":"Or that the child is an American citizen and has an American passport, and incidentally I believe he is also a Greek citizen.","start":2073.027,"stop":2080.07,"duration":7.04},{"text":"I believe he is a dual national.","start":2080.07,"stop":2086.967,"duration":6.9},{"text":"I should like to turn now to the -- the consideration of the -- whether the -- the one sentence in the Board's opinion on reconsideration was improper.","start":2086.967,"stop":2108.46,"duration":21.49},{"text":"The Board there merely referred to the 1952 Act and its background without indicating in any way that it considered itself inhibited by that.","start":2108.46,"stop":2120.907,"duration":12.45},{"text":"We -- we construe that as the court below did as merely indicating that its decision was consonant with the 1952 Act, rather than dictated by the Act.","start":2120.907,"stop":2132.896,"duration":11.99},{"text":"But as I pointed out the -- the statute did not set any limits on the considerations which might be taken into account by the Attorney General in weighing his discretion.","start":2132.896,"stop":2147.071,"duration":14.17},{"text":"And it seems to me that it's quite proper for the Attorney General to take into account the feeling of Congress and the observations of Congress made after a long study.","start":2147.071,"stop":2160.082,"duration":13.01},{"text":"Now, the 1952 Act and I might point out that we agree that 1917 Act governs this case.","start":2160.082,"stop":2170.517,"duration":10.43},{"text":"But the 1952 Act was a long time aborning.","start":2170.517,"stop":2175.76,"duration":5.24},{"text":"Congress, I believe it was in 1948, authorized the Senate Judiciary Committee to make a study of the way the immigration laws were operating.","start":2175.76,"stop":2184.557,"duration":8.8},{"text":"And they made a very intensive study, which resulted in Senate Report 1515 which this Court has referred to in many opinions.","start":2184.557,"stop":2193.663,"duration":9.11},{"text":"That was an elaborate report and it dissected the operations of the immigrations laws and the manner in which the Immigration Service had administered those laws.","start":2193.663,"stop":2207.492,"duration":13.83},{"text":"That study came out in 1950 while the 1917 Act was still operative.","start":2207.492,"stop":2214.771,"duration":7.28},{"text":"And as a result of that study various bills were introduced, which finally culminated and in the McCarran-Walter Act which is the 1952 Act.","start":2214.771,"stop":2224.328,"duration":9.56},{"text":"And its -- in its consideration of these bills, Congress had various reports in which it commented.","start":2224.328,"stop":2230.287,"duration":5.96},{"text":"It gave its views on what it considered the inadequacy of the old law and also it was critical of the manner in which the old law had been executed in some respects.","start":2230.287,"stop":2243.583,"duration":13.3},{"text":"Now, we must bear in mind that the Attorney General's power to suspend is not the final word in these cases, because Congress has reserved to itself something which is more than a veto power.","start":2243.583,"stop":2260.605,"duration":17.02},{"text":"If the Attorney General -- and this is under 1917 Act as well as under the 1952 Act, if the Attorney General suspends deportation in any case, he must refer the facts to the Congress and unless Congress affirmatively passes a concurrent resolution approving that suspension that all is for naught and the Attorney General is commanded to proceed with deportation.","start":2260.605,"stop":2287.092,"duration":26.49}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there a time within which Congress must so act?","start":2287.092,"stop":2289.57,"duration":2.48}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2289.57,"stop":2290.489,"duration":0.92},{"text":"The concurrent resolution must be passed either at the session at which a report is made or at the next session.","start":2290.489,"stop":2298.602,"duration":8.11},{"text":"And the Act specifies that if by the close of the next session such a concurrent resolution has not been passed, the Attorney General shall proceed with deportation.","start":2298.602,"stop":2310.745,"duration":12.14},{"text":"So that it is Congress which has the last word and it would be very odd if Congress should have intended that the Attorney General could take into consideration various factors in weighing his discretion, but should be precluded from taking into account the views of Congress.","start":2310.745,"stop":2335.409,"duration":24.66},{"text":"We feel that -- that the Attorney General acted properly.","start":2335.409,"stop":2340.769,"duration":5.36},{"text":"The Attorney General acting through its Board, acted properly if it took into account the current policy of the Congress, but we feel that when read in context, this one sentence in the Board's opinion on reopening, does not detract from the fact that the Board exercised its discretion completely in consonance with the theory of the 1940 Act.","start":2340.769,"stop":2374.253,"duration":33.48},{"text":"And that its reference to the 1952 Act was merely, one might say a makeweight, another reason for saying this is not a case to reopen.","start":2374.253,"stop":2384.193,"duration":9.94}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Roberts (Inaudible)","start":2384.193,"stop":2389.804,"duration":5.61}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"The 1952 Act simply narrowed the range of discretion by setting up more rigorous standards of eligibility.","start":2389.804,"stop":2399.192,"duration":9.39},{"text":"For example, these petitioners could not qualify for suspension under the 1952 Act, because the 1952 Act require 10 years of continuous presence in the United States.","start":2399.192,"stop":2412.276,"duration":13.08},{"text":"They didn't have it.","start":2412.276,"stop":2412.861,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2412.861,"stop":2414.691,"duration":1.83}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":2414.691,"stop":2415.138,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- (Inaudible)","start":2415.138,"stop":2419.093,"duration":3.95}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":2419.093,"stop":2419.712,"duration":0.62},{"text":"Except to the extent that in -- in enlarging the ineligible classes, the 1952 Act cut down on the cases in which the Attorney General could exercise --","start":2419.712,"stop":2432.136,"duration":12.42}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2432.136,"stop":2436.828,"duration":4.69}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no, and as a matter of fact, the 1952 Act set up no yardstick to govern the Attorney General in exercising his discretion.","start":2436.828,"stop":2446.44,"duration":9.61}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The Attorney General's -- the Attorney General's discretion after eligibility of discretion under the 1952 statute was different between the time (Inaudible)","start":2446.44,"stop":2456.754,"duration":10.31}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Not at all, not at all.","start":2456.754,"stop":2458.288,"duration":1.53},{"text":"We believe that that discretion is discretion and that the Attorney General is entitled to weigh the relevant factors.","start":2458.288,"stop":2466.388,"duration":8.1},{"text":"And in fact, there -- there has been a succession of the Attorney's General since the 1940 Act was put on the books.","start":2466.388,"stop":2474.281,"duration":7.89},{"text":"And some they have felt that their predecessors were a -- a little too lenient or perhaps a little too restrictive in their grant of discretion.","start":2474.281,"stop":2482.041,"duration":7.76},{"text":"But that was a matter -- that was within their compass and in fact we had a change of administration since the 1952 Act went into effect.","start":2482.041,"stop":2493.438,"duration":11.4},{"text":"But these -- these are -- are matters which are within the -- the field of expertise, which Congress has left to the administrative authorities who are best qualified to make judgments in this field.","start":2493.438,"stop":2508.167,"duration":14.73}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Roberts, how many application for suspension during the (Inaudible) one of these years were there, of the total applications and the total number of granted or rejected?","start":2508.167,"stop":2519.343,"duration":11.18},{"text":"Have you got those figures (Voice Overlap) --","start":2519.343,"stop":2520.296,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"I have the figures for the last few years, Your Honor.","start":2520.296,"stop":2522.448,"duration":2.15}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And you might be good enough to give them?","start":2522.448,"stop":2524.072,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2524.072,"stop":2525.665,"duration":1.59},{"text":"And I may say this, that they demonstrate that since the 1952 Act with its more restrictive standards, there's been a marked (Inaudible) For the fiscal year ending June 30, 1956, 1021 cases were submitted to Congress and Congress approved 1088.","start":2525.665,"stop":2548.846,"duration":23.18},{"text":"You may note that Congress approved more than were submitted but that's because they are -- there are backlogs carrying over from one session to the next.","start":2548.846,"stop":2556.89,"duration":8.04},{"text":"In the year 1955, 1089 were submitted by the Immigration Service and 1937 were approved by Congress.","start":2556.89,"stop":2569.297,"duration":12.41},{"text":"In the year 1954, 2241 were submitted by the Immigration Service and 6035 were approved by Congress.","start":2569.297,"stop":2582.402,"duration":13.11}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, when you give the figure of 1021, are those where the Attorney General exercised his discretion in favor of suspension?","start":2582.402,"stop":2589.868,"duration":7.47},{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2589.868,"stop":2590.38,"duration":0.51},{"text":"What I would like to know is how many applications have been made to him, the total sum of which 1021 were those that were favorably considered.","start":2590.38,"stop":2599.852,"duration":9.47},{"text":"I don't have the figures on that sir.","start":2599.852,"stop":2601.842,"duration":1.99}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2601.842,"stop":2603.069,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't know whether those statistics are maintained.","start":2603.069,"stop":2605.835,"duration":2.77}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean the denials are not afforded in statistics?","start":2605.835,"stop":2611.561,"duration":5.73},{"text":"But there are denials, aren't there?","start":2611.561,"stop":2612.882,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"There -- there are denials as this case demonstrates.","start":2612.882,"stop":2615.96,"duration":3.08}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2615.96,"stop":2618.438,"duration":2.48}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I shall be very happy to make inquiry --","start":2618.438,"stop":2621.38,"duration":2.94},{"text":"But if isn't -- it isn't worthwhile to make any extent here to put any load, heavy load, but if they're just ready all you can do is to take them off from some sheet then I would like to see them.","start":2621.38,"stop":2632.276,"duration":10.9}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that -- that is where these figures were obtained from --","start":2632.276,"stop":2633.495,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, that they probably -- they must have the number of applications, not merely applications granted, actually describe that they didn't.","start":2633.495,"stop":2640.285,"duration":6.79}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"However --","start":2640.285,"stop":2641.269,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"I'll -- I'll try to supply the Court with that.","start":2641.269,"stop":2643.18,"duration":1.91}]},{"speakerName":"Stanley Reed","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2643.18,"stop":2646.12,"duration":2.94}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"No, the denials are not required to be reported.","start":2646.12,"stop":2648.249,"duration":2.13}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":2648.249,"stop":2649.652,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"Stanley Reed","textObjs":[{"text":"When did they -- that requirement first come in the statute that the Attorney General had to report the ones he recommended?","start":2649.652,"stop":2656.353,"duration":6.7}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Right in the initial statute in 1940.","start":2656.353,"stop":2658.814,"duration":2.46}]},{"speakerName":"Stanley Reed","textObjs":[{"text":"1940?","start":2658.814,"stop":2659.606,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2659.606,"stop":2660.179,"duration":0.57},{"text":"In fact, the -- the debates on the 1940 measure, that is in the background of the 1940 Act, indicated clearly that the Congress didn't want to leave the ultimate discretion to the -- to the Secretary of Labor at that time.","start":2660.179,"stop":2673.68,"duration":13.5},{"text":"They wanted to reserve to themselves the power to have the final say.","start":2673.68,"stop":2679.423,"duration":5.74}]},{"speakerName":"Stanley Reed","textObjs":[{"text":"Does Congress turn it -- it down, do you have --","start":2679.423,"stop":2682.371,"duration":2.95}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2682.371,"stop":2683.176,"duration":0.8},{"text":"As -- as a matter fact, one of the Board decisions points out that the 81st Congress, within a period of several months, had turned down 37 cases, all involving the same pattern, that is aliens from contiguous territory who would come here and then -- who would come here recently.","start":2683.176,"stop":2704.476,"duration":21.3},{"text":"And then had had a child born here and applied for suspension on the basis of that birth.","start":2704.476,"stop":2710.523,"duration":6.05},{"text":"And incidentally, the Attorney General had suspended deportation on those cases and Congress had turned every one of them down.","start":2710.523,"stop":2718.651,"duration":8.13}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"If these -- these recommendations go to the commission -- Committee on Immigration in the House?","start":2718.651,"stop":2725.137,"duration":6.49}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2725.137,"stop":2727.358,"duration":2.22}]},{"speakerName":"Stanley Reed","textObjs":[{"text":"What year is that?","start":2727.358,"stop":2728.854,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg your pardon?","start":2728.854,"stop":2729.451,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Stanley Reed","textObjs":[{"text":"What year is that, they turned down those (Inaudible)","start":2729.451,"stop":2731.481,"duration":2.03}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe that was in the 81st Congress.","start":2731.481,"stop":2734.101,"duration":2.62},{"text":"I believe -- I -- I have a reference --","start":2734.101,"stop":2735.826,"duration":1.72}]},{"speakerName":"Stanley Reed","textObjs":[{"text":"Until 19 --","start":2735.826,"stop":2736.018,"duration":0.19}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"-- to the case.","start":2736.018,"stop":2738.04,"duration":2.02}]},{"speakerName":"Stanley Reed","textObjs":[{"text":"About 1948?","start":2738.04,"stop":2739.524,"duration":1.48}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"It was -- it was before the 1952 Act.","start":2739.524,"stop":2743.944,"duration":4.42}]},{"speakerName":"Stanley Reed","textObjs":[{"text":"1949 (Inaudible)","start":2743.944,"stop":2746.609,"duration":2.66}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if that the precedent then they even had the least petitioners had been granted an order, it might well be that Congress (Inaudible)","start":2746.609,"stop":2756.78,"duration":10.17}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"It -- it's possible that Congress -- Congress there has not hesitated to -- to turn down cases were it felt that the Attorney General has perhaps been a little too lenient.","start":2756.78,"stop":2768.044,"duration":11.26}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I thought you said there -- what -- whatever number of cases you've just given the 1948 were turned down, a number were turned down because there has been a child born shortly after they arrived?","start":2768.044,"stop":2778.95,"duration":10.91}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2778.95,"stop":2779.687,"duration":0.74},{"text":"I must say in all fairness that -- that there were other factors.","start":2779.687,"stop":2781.352,"duration":1.66},{"text":"That was merely one of the factors involved in these cases.","start":2781.352,"stop":2787.682,"duration":6.33},{"text":"They were -- they were aliens from contiguous territory.","start":2787.682,"stop":2791.075,"duration":3.39},{"text":"I assume Mexicans and they had come here with large families, and they applied for a suspension of deportation because of the fact that after arriving here they had had a child born here.","start":2791.075,"stop":2802.548,"duration":11.47},{"text":"And on the basis of that child being an American citizen, the -- the Attorney General or that his delegate, the Board, had suspended deportation.","start":2802.548,"stop":2813.08,"duration":10.53},{"text":"And Congress had in 37 cases, following the same pattern simply refused to go along.","start":2813.08,"stop":2818.516,"duration":5.44}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"If I get him, I have a faint recollection of the Congressman -- representative ordered -- keeps a sharp eye on his business.","start":2818.516,"stop":2825.66,"duration":7.14}]},{"speakerName":"Maurice A. Roberts","textObjs":[{"text":"A very sharp eye.","start":2825.66,"stop":2832.959,"duration":7.3},{"text":"We submit that in this case the record makes it clear that the Board did not fail to exercise its discretion.","start":2832.959,"stop":2842.663,"duration":9.7},{"text":"That in exercising its discretion it did not act arbitrarily and that in -- in weighing the factors, which go to make up discretion, it did not take into account anything that it should not have.","start":2842.663,"stop":2859.472,"duration":16.81},{"text":"We believe the judgment below should be affirmed.","start":2859.472,"stop":2863.009,"duration":3.54}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Long, do you have some rebuttal?","start":2863.009,"stop":2866.029,"duration":3.02}]},{"speakerName":"Jay Nicholas Long","textObjs":[{"text":"I just like, if Your -- Your Honor please, to make two points out.","start":2866.029,"stop":2871.383,"duration":5.35},{"text":"First of all, Mr. Justice Brennan, had raised the question as to the factors considered by the Board in granting suspension of deportation under the Act of 1917.","start":2871.383,"stop":2881.553,"duration":10.17},{"text":"I'd like to invite attention to pages 15, 16 and 17 of my brief, concerning the fact as that -- that they have taken into consideration because they have been quite flexible on -- on that including granting suspension of deportation to a woman who being here as a visitor, married an illegal alien one month after she was here.","start":2881.553,"stop":2906.473,"duration":24.92},{"text":"And then once a child was born applied for suspension of deportation, it was granted her.","start":2906.473,"stop":2912.009,"duration":5.54},{"text":"And the emphasis there by the Board was on the fact that her deportation would work on incredible hardship or serious detriment to the child if its parent was taken or was sent abroad.","start":2912.009,"stop":2926.062,"duration":14.05},{"text":"That is just one case that I think is -- is more of an emphatic on -- in favor of the petitioners here.","start":2926.062,"stop":2933.989,"duration":7.93},{"text":"And Mr. Justice Clark concerning the question raised by you as to the cases turned down by the Congress had been recommended by the Attorney General.","start":2933.989,"stop":2947.306,"duration":13.32},{"text":"I would like to point out that immediately before the enactment of the -- the Act in 1952, the judiciary committees of both Houses had decided to put a clamp on the thousands of cases that were being recommended for suspension of deportation principally, in connection with aliens who had been caught here during the war and had stayed here for seven years or more and hence, were eligible for suspension of deportation under the amendment of the Act of 1948, which said that aliens here for seven years or more were eligible for that period.","start":2947.306,"stop":2985.432,"duration":38.13},{"text":"And that Congress at that time in considering the Act of 1952 took the position that we are not going to place a lot of load or reap on the -- of reward of all these thousands of aliens who had successfully evaded our laws for seven years or more.","start":2985.432,"stop":3003.749,"duration":18.32},{"text":"But, of course, I think that that is a very serious distinction from cases such as the one at bar where the welfare of an American citizen was the principal consideration.","start":3003.749,"stop":3014.164,"duration":10.42},{"text":"But the truth is that at -- at the time that the Board was considering this case, several thousand cases had been rejected by the Congress.","start":3014.164,"stop":3024.878,"duration":10.71},{"text":"And thus -- and the Board had before it the problem of trying to dispose of all of these cases administratively by way of having thrown back in their lap by the Congress.","start":3024.878,"stop":3036.347,"duration":11.47},{"text":"And I'm sure that was a very important consideration for the Board at the time that it considered this particular case, even though it did not say so in its decision.","start":3036.347,"stop":3048.908,"duration":12.56}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Long.","start":3048.908,"stop":3058.583,"duration":9.68}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Warren Court","arguedOn":"Mar 4, 1957","petitioner":"United States ex rel. Hintopoulos","respondent":"Shaughnessy","docket":"205","citation":"353 US 72 (1957)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/353/72","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Mar 25, 1957"}